<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Rejects U.S. Overture as "Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Supreme leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei Sunday rejected the recent U.S. overture as a "normal
political hypocritical ploy."
</P>
<P>
Khamenei made the remarks in a speech to mark the birthday of
Islam's Prophet Mohammad, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Secretary of State Madelaine
Albright said last month that Washington is ready to end 20-year
hostility with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei said Washington's overture was based on its
miscalculated analysis of Iran's domestic political situation.
</P>
<P>
Washington's overture came at a time when the hard-line faction
was locked in a mounting power struggle with moderates clustered
around President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Khatami has taken measures to lessen hostility with Washington,
including non-official exchange between the two countries, since
his inauguration last year.
</P>
<P>
But Khamenei said in the speech that as long as Iran kept its
Muslim identity and remained committed to Palestinians in their
struggle against Israel, Washington would not give up its "harsh
and rude enmity toward Iran."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that despite all the endeavors of some elements to
generate dissension among the people, the Iranian nation, the
government, the officials and the people of all strata are united
in their ideals for making the Islamic revolution successful.
</P>
<P>
Iran has always been and will remain an ardent follower of
Islamic ideals, protector of its values, and dispenser of its
teachings while maintaining its strong support for the Palestinian
cause and Islamic unity, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
