<HEADLINE> Mandela's Ex-Wife Denies Leaving ANC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Winnie Madikikizela-Mandela,
ex-wife of South African President Nelson Mandela Sunday
categorically denied the reports that she intended
to quit the ruling African National Congress (ANC).
</P>
<P>
"I am the ANC and I will die as the ANC," she said in a
statement sent to South African Press Association (SAPA) office
in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the Sunday Times reported that Madikikizela-Mandela,
current leader of the ANC Women's League, had sent a letter to
the party's leadership, threatening to quit the National
Executive Committee, citing bad treatment at the hands of top ANC
members.
</P>
<P>
Among the leaders mentioned were Sports Minister Steve Tshwete
who last year wrote an article calling her a "liar" and "a
wayward charlatan."
</P>
<P>
This was after she publicly criticized the ANC for failing to
address crimes, land redistribution and the shortage of housing.
</P>
</TEXT>
