<HEADLINE> Zambian Govt to Consult with Striking Magistrates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government will start
consultations t7is week with the Magistrates and Judges
Association of Zambia to resolve the on-going strike by
magistrates.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Sunday quoted Vincent Malambo, legal affairs
minister, as saying in an interview here Saturday that he will
meet leaders of the association for consultations on ways of
ending the strike which entered its 10th day.
</P>
<P>
Malambo retreated from his earlier statement that the
government will not condone the strike because it is illegal and
that the association is merely an association and has nothing to
do with the conditions of services.
</P>
<P>
He said he is busy working toward getting the magistrates back
to work. However, he did not elaborate but said that he is
positive that the problem will be resolved.
</P>
<P>
"I am saying that the problem will be solved. We can't have an
indefinite strike and allow cases to pile up in courts, work has
to go on," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, magistrates in the capital of Lusaka, the
country's tourist capital of Livingstone and Copperbelt Province
began to strike to press for better conditions of service.
</P>
<P>
They hihe warned the government that the strike will go on
indefinitely until their requirements are met. 
</P>
</TEXT>
