<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, IMF Agree on Basic Issues of Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko and a delegation from the International Monetary Fund
have "agreed on all key issues" on a multi-billion-U.S.-dollar
financial bailout for Russia, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko's meeting with the delegation led by John
Odling-Smee, head of the IMF department responsible for the former
Soviet Union ended later Sunday, Itar-Tass said quoting a
government source.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also attended by Russian President Boris
Yeltsin's top negotiator with international financial
organizations Anatoly Chubais, head of the Central Bank Sergei
Dubinin and Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko and Odling-Smee agreed that details of the agreement
reached during Sunday's talks will be disclosed on Monday,
Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times reported Sunday that the IMF had told
Russian officials that it was ready to lend Moscow 11 billion U.S.
dollars, nearly double the 5.6 billion dollars initially
discussed.
</P>
<P>
Chubais has said that his country, beset by poor tax
collections, low world oil prices and financial market
turbulences, need 10-15 billion dollars in urgent loans.
</P>
<P>
In May, foreign investors fled Russian financial markets and
the stock market fell about 50 percent of its value since the
beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
Russia hopes that the loans will help it tide over the current
difficulties and prop up the ruble, which is under increasing
pressure to devaluate, though the government insists that no
devaluation would be allowed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-12 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Not to Renegotiate on U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Senior Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat stressed Sunday that the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) will never re-negotiate the 13 percent Israeli
troops withdrawal proposed by the U.S., Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a political seminar here, Erekat said that 99
percent of the American initiative, which calls for a 13 percent
Israeli redeployment in the West Bank, is in fact "(Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin) Netanyahu's initiative."
</P>
<P>
The PNA has accepted the American initiative, although it falls
far short of the minimum Palestinian demands, in what Palestinian
officials say is an effort to rescue the moribund peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Netanyahu must hear me very clearly ... the figure (13
percent) would never be re-negotiated. This is Saeb Erekat
speaking on behalf of (PNA President Yasser) Arafat, Abu Mazen
(PNA deputy head), (Palestinian General Security Commander
Mohammed) Dahlan, (and) everyone (else)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Erekat was actually reacting to an American call for direct
Israeli-Palestinian talks over the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials believe that the U.S., frustrated by its
failure to resolve disputes with Israel over the 13 percent
initiative, urged the direct talks to be renewed in a bid to allow
the two sides to directly discuss Israel's proposals concerning
the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
After the direct talks broke down 16 months ago when Israel
began to build a Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem, Israel
and the U.S. have been engaged in a lengthy bargain over the
American initiative but it was reported that disputes over the
pullback scope remain.
</P>
<P>
A latest report said that the recent discussions between
U.S. Middle East envoy Dennis Ross and Israeli negotiator Yitzhak
Molcho in New York have failed. Israel demanded that 3 percent of
the 13 percent go with special construction and zoning
restrictions for the Palestinians, but the U.S. rejected the idea
under Palestinian protests, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It was under this circumstance, among other things, that
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright last week called on
Israel and the Palestinians to resume direct contact, saying
progress is impossible without it.
</P>
<P>
Israel has expressed satisfaction that the U.S. backed a key
Israeli demand for direct talks as a mechanism to resolve the
existing problems. Its suggestion that direct talks be renewed has
been rejected more than once by the PNA, which says what Israel
needs to do is to accept the U.S. proposal.
</P>
<P>
Erekat stressed at the seminar that the PNA would not agree to
any change to the U.S. initiative, warning the U.S. that if it
wants the direct talks to be resumed in order to allow the
initiative renegotiated, then the PNA would make its own new
demands.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the U.S. to make public its views over who should
be blamed for the current impasse in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Reopen Land Tribunals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
decided to reopen land tribunals so as to end land disputes in
the northern region of Arusha, President Benjamin Mkapa said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During a tour to Arusha Region, Mkapa said he wants to see the
end of the land conflicts before the next farming season.
</P>
<P>
The decision to reactivate the tribunals has been prompted by
the prevailing land conflicts and pileup of land cases, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the cash-strapped tribunals will be financed by the
State Emergency Fund, according to a news dispatch reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president urged the judiciary to speed up the
hearing of land cases.
</P>
<P>
Violent incidences resulted from land disputes have persisted
for a long time in Arusha. There are 200 outstanding land cases
in the region at present.
</P>
<P>
During the tour, the president also gave green light to native
livestock keepers to engage in farming in the Ngorongoro
Conservation Area so as to maintain their basic life.
</P>
<P>
But he insisted that non-natives and farmers bent solely on
profit are not allowed to undertake agricultural activities in
the area.
</P>
<P>
Any people who ignore the ban will be punished by the law, he
added.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the government allowed subsistence farming in the
area. However, the privilege was abused by commercial farmers
coming from other places.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
