<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Tries to Curb Dumping of Goods From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government decided to
set up an anti-dumping committee to curb the dumping of
foreign goods into the country.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Zambia Association of Manufacturers (ZAM),
Mark O'donnel, told the Zambia News Agency Sunday that the
manufacturing sector welcomes the government's intention to set
up the anti-dumping committee to protect local manufacturers from
the adverse effect of the dumping.
</P>
<P>
O'donnel said that the local manufacturers have for sometime
now been facing stiff competition from low quality imported
commodities sold on Zambian markets at very low prices.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to focus on the adverse effect of
subsidized goods because many local companies are closing down as
a result of the presence of the competing commodities.
</P>
<P>
The patent and copyright laws should be strengthened in order
to effectively deal with rampant forgery and imitations of
products by unscrupulous businessmen, said O'donnel.
</P>
<P>
He said the proposed legislation aimed at dealing with the
dumping of foreign products will not serve its purpose if law
enforcement agents do not implement the laws.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturers should be part of the composition of the
anti-dumping committee so that they can advise the government on
the best way to deal with the scourge, O'donnel added.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Ackim Nkole, the Zambian Deputy Minister of
Commerce, Trade and Industry, said that the government was in the
process of establishing an anti-dumping committee that would
consider making changes to legislation to effectively deal with
the dumping of foreign goods in the country.
</P>
<P>
Also last week, President Frederick Chiluba said that his
government will sign trade agreements with neighboring countries
so as to protect its local industries threatened by imported
subsidized goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
