<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Awarded 1998 Hunger Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The 1998 Africa prize for
Leadership for the Sustainable End of Hunger has gone to Ugandan
President Yoweri Kaguta Museveni and Mrs. Celina Cossa of
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The two prize winners were announced at a special announcement
ceremony held in Blantyre, Malawi, Saturday by former United
Nations Secretary-General Dr. Perez De Cuellar who is chair of
the Award's international jury in a recorded message. The
ceremony was presided over by Malawian President Dr. Bakili
Muluzi, the Malawi News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Award carries a prize-money of 100,000 U.S. Dollars. The
Africa prize for Leadership for Sustainable End of Hunger is
under the New York based "hunger project".
</P>
<P>
De Cuellar said Museveni, apart from establishing peace and
democracy in his country, has also put in place sound economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
"These policies, together with his commitment to the
well-being of his people, have created the enabling environment
which has made Uganda one of the best performers in Africa in
terms of economic development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cossa was chosen due to her struggle and hard work in creating
cooperatives in Mozambique which have played a critical role in
reducing hunger and malnutrition in Mozambique, particularly in
Maputo area through increased food production.
</P>
<P>
"She is leader of the General Union of Agriculture
Cooperatives (GUAC), an organisation that has got 10,000 peasants
of whom 95 percent are women," said De Cuellar. There are 200
cooperatives under the GUAC.
</P>
<P>
Last year's prize of 100,000 Dollars was shared between
Malawi's Joyce Banda, founder and chief executive of National
Association of Business Women of Malawi (NABW), and Mozambican
President Joaquim Chissano.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the function, President Muluzi said, for Africa to
eradicate hunger, it needs to enhance food production and
increase the purchasing power among the people.
</P>
<P>
"Intensifying research on high yielding varieties that are
suitable for tropical African conditions and developing
inexpensive irrigation systems that can be replicate throughout
the country could be other ways of achieving food security on the
continent," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Above all, since hunger is primarily a consequence of
poverty, we need to promote rapid, broad-based economic
development, with rapid job creation and rising productivity,"
Muluzi noted.
</P>
<P>
The Africa prize, said the president, is refreshingly unique
in that it puts the spotlight for change on the positive
achievements and breakthroughs that are happening throughout
Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The hunger project is a welcome catalyst to Africa's on-going
national efforts aimed at empowering and developing her
citizens," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Malawian president added that his government is striving
to eradicate hunger through the poverty alleviation program, the
country's centerpiece of economic development which aims at
reducing poverty and at the same time empowering people
economically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
