<HEADLINE> Greece Unhappy Over Turkish Warplanes' Training in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Greece on Monday expressed its
unwillingness to reports of an exercise involving Turkish
warplanes at an Israeli base designed to destroy the S-300
anti-aircraft missiles which will be delivered by Russia to Cyprus
later this year.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the reports of the exercise, Greek government
spokesman Dimitris Reppas said that if the press reports were
correct, it would be an example of offering bad services to
relations between the countries of the region and in general, to
peace and security in the southeast Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
He also reaffirmed that Greece supported multilateral
cooperation in the region and against the creation of axes.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli embassy in Athens Monday denied reports on the
exercise, saying that the reports had no basis in reality.
</P>
<P>
Israel's cooperation with countries in the region was not
directed against third parties and certainly not against Greece or
Cyprus, a press release from the embassy said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern third of the island following a Greek-Cypriot coup in
Nicosia seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Tensions on the island have risen markedly as the planned
deployment date for the Russian-made missiles approaches.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has warned that it will use force to prevent deployment
of the missiles because they threaten the security in both Turkey
and northern Cyprus, which declared independence in 1983 but
recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Chief of Staff General Ismail Karadayi visited
northern Cyprus at the weekend and met with Turkish-Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash for talks reportedly on possible counter-measures to
any deployment of the missiles.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides is now in Moscow
for talks with the Russian leadership, including President Boris
Yeltsin, on issues concerning the deployment of the missiles, but
he has made it clear that delivery of the missiles could be
delayed if Turkish Cypriots resumed negotiations and progress was
made on the issue that have kept the island republic divided.
</P>
</TEXT>
