<HEADLINE> Hashimoto, Kiriyenko Agree to Boost Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto and his Russian counterpart Sergei Kiriyenko agreed
Monday to further strengthen bilateral ties with an expansion of
economic cooperation despite domestic political turmoil in both
countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during an hour-long meeting between
Hashimoto and Kiriyenko after Hashimoto announced his resignation
as prime minister Monday afternoon to take responsibility for his
Liberal Democratic Party's major setback in Sunday's House of
Councillors election.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that (bilateral relations) will not change whatever
changes occur in Japan's political situation and Russia's domestic
politics," Kiriyenko told a news conference after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
On the ongoing bilateral negotiations for the conclusion of a
peace treaty by the year 2000 through the resolution of a
decades-old territorial row over Russian-held islands, Hashimoto
said he and Kiriyenko reaffirmed the importance of accelerating
the diplomatic process.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto reassured Kiriyenko that bilateral ties would be
strengthened no matter who succeeds him as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In his separate talks with Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo
Obuchi, Kiriyenko sought further Japanese economic assistance by
expanding the cooperation programs as part of efforts to overcome
Russia's financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also agreed to step up bilateral cooperation,
especially in trade and economic areas, Japanese officials said.
</P>
<P>
After their talks, the two countries signed an unofficial
memorandum on a new agreement to protect and promote Japanese
private-sector investment in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko arrived here earlier in the day for a two-day visit
to Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
