<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Sends Message to AL Chief on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdel-Meguid Monday received a message from
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat on
the long freeze of negotiations on the Palestinian-Israeli track.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid was handed the message during a meeting with Asaad
Abdel-Rahman, PLO Executive Committee member in charge of the
refugees file, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The message, whose content is not available, also dealt with
the conditions of Palestinian refugees in Arab countries and in
Shaafat refugee camp, the only one in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians in Shaafat refugee camp have been over the
past 12 days the "butt of ethnic cleansing, arrests, shootings and
other intimidating practices" by Israeli forces, Abdel-Rahman told
reporters following his meeting with the AL chief.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official said the AL chief promised to make
intensive contacts at the highest level with the parties
concerned in order to press the Israeli government to stop such
practices in the interest of the future of the Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Rahman asked the U.S. to persuade Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's government to reconsider its intransigent
policy.
</P>
<P>
He said Palestinians have only "reluctantly" agreed to the 13
percent Israeli pullback from the West Bank as prescribed in the
latest U.S. initiative. In any fresh Palestinian-Israeli
negotiations, he said, the Palestinian side will ask Israel to
withdraw from 40 percent of West Bank territory in line with the
agreements signed with Israel.
</P>
<P>
As the key Mideast peace broker, the U.S. said last week that
it was pressing the two sides to negotiate directly. The New York
Times reported Sunday that Israeli and U.S. officials expected
negotiations on the proposed pullback to conclude by the end of
July but were not sure if the talks would come up with a deal.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have ruled out making any changes in the
U.S.-and Palestinian-backed proposal for a 13 percent Israeli
withdrawal. Netanyahu has for months resisted the plan.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Rahman is currently in Cairo to preside over a five-day
conference of supervisors of Palestinian affairs in some Arab
countries that host Palestinian communities. The meeting opened at
the Arab League headquarters here on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
