<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, July 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- The traditional march of Northern Ireland's
Protestant residents in Belfast, known as the Orange Parade,
passed off peacefully Monday morning amid tensions created by a
bomb alert and a murder one day ago.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 marchers walked in silence along the Ormeau Road,
which passes through Belfast's Catholic neighborhood, while
hundreds of other Protestants watched along the route, reported
BBC TV news.
</P>
<P>
The planed parade had caused violence and tensions lately
between Belfast's Protestant and Catholic residents, with the
Catholics regarding it as a provocative move.
</P>
<P>
The march finally took place after local Catholic residents
agreed to stage only a "dignified" silent protest to the parade.
(N.Ireland-Orange Parade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and his
Russian counterpart Sergei Kiriyenko agreed Monday to further
strengthen bilateral ties with an expansion of economic
cooperation despite domestic political turmoil in both countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during an hour-long meeting between
Hashimoto and Kiriyenko after Hashimoto announced his resignation
as prime minister Monday afternoon to take responsibility for his
Liberal Democratic Party's major setback in Sunday's House of
Councillors election.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that (bilateral relations) will not change whatever
changes occur in Japan's political situation and Russia's domestic
politics," Kiriyenko told a news conference after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
On the ongoing bilateral negotiations for the conclusion of a
peace treaty by the year 2000 through the resolution of a
decades-old territorial row over Russian-held islands, Hashimoto
said he and Kiriyenko reaffirmed the importance of accelerating
the diplomatic process. (Japan-Russia-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Palestinian Legislative Council (PLC) Monday
granted Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat two more weeks to form a
new Cabinet, the PLC Information Office told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
At a semimonthly session held in the West Bank city of
Ramallah, PLC Speaker Abu Ala read out a letter written to the
council by Arafat, who asked for another extension of time for him
to complete the reshuffle of the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA).
</P>
<P>
The PLC agreed to accept Arafat's request and demanded that he
announce the new lineup of the cabinet by July 25.
</P>
<P>
The PNA Cabinet resigned on June 24 after the PLC threatened to
hold a no-confidence vote against it over charges of corruption
and improper allocation of the 1998 budget.
(Palestine-Legislature-Cabinet Reshuffle) 
</P>
</TEXT>
