<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Reaffirms Commitment to One-China Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- President Joseph Estrada here
Monday reaffirmed the Philippine government's commitment to the
one-China policy and assured Beijing that his administration will
not support Taiwan's bid for independence.
</P>
<P>
After a courtesy call on the President, Chinese ambassador Guan
Dengming said President Estrada was "very positive and supportive
of the one-China policy."
</P>
<P>
And this is in line with the "Three-No" policies expressed
earlier by U.S. President Bill Clinton in China -- no to Taiwan
independence, no to one-China, one-Taiwan or two-China policy, and
no to Taiwan's membership to any international organization where
"sovereignty is required," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has been bound by the one-China
policy which recognizes the People's Republic of China as the only
Chinese sovereign state and treats Taiwan only as a province of
the People's Republic of China, the Philippine News Agency
reported on the same day.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Guan also said that during the call, President
Estrada and he focused their talk on "how to develop a good
neighborly partnership" between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"President Estrada expressed his wish to continue to develop a
friendly relationship with China. I also expressed our long
standing policy to further strengthen our direct relationship,"
Guan said, adding that it has been the long-standing policy of the
Chinese government to further develop its diplomatic ties with its
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada said China will be the first country he will
visit.
</P>
<P>
Guan, on behalf of the Chinese government, expressed his
welcome and invited Estrada to visit China at his convenient
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
