<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Meets Arafat in Beijing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Arafat briefed Jiang on the latest developments in talks
between Palestine and Israel, as well as the Middle East peace
process. He stressed that the Palestinian side hopes that the
Israeli government will abide by existing peace agreements,
abandon its hard-line policy, and join the international community
in breaking the current deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Palestine sincerely hopes that Israel's peace talks with all
parties, including Palestine, Syria, and Lebanon, will achieve
progress, and a lasting peace will be finally achieved in the
Middle East, said Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the Palestinian issue is the core of the Middle
East issue centering on the world's longest pending hot
spot. China has always been closely concerned with the Middle East
peace process, especially peace talks between Palestine and
Israel, and greatly appreciates Palestine's principled stance for
a solution through peaceful negotiations.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to support the efforts of Palestinian
people to regain their legitimate rights, including the
establishment of an independent state, said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
The just cause of Palestinian people will win even greater
sympathy and support from the world community during continuing
peace talks, said Jiang, adding that China, a permanent member of
the UN Security Council, will join the rest of the world in
pushing forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also briefed Arafat on China's resumption of sovereignty
over Hong Kong and the nation's foreign policy. Arafat said the
smooth transfer of Hong Kong fully demonstrates the wisdom and
success of the "one country, two systems" policy.
</P>
<P>
Jiang presided over a welcoming ceremony for Arafat earlier in
the day, and the talks concluded with the two governments signing
an agreement on economic and technological cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
