<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abkhazia Condemns Terrorist Attack on Russian Peacekeepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The breakaway republic of Abkhazia
Monday denounced a terrorist attack on Sunday night, in which five
Russian peacekeeping soldiers died and three more injured.
</P>
<P>
According to Interfax news agency, Abkhazian Foreign Minister
Sergei Shamba condemned the attack as an attempt to thwart peace
talks between Abkhazia and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Abkhazia, seeking independence from Georgia, has been in armed
conflicts with the Georgian government since 1991.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday night, a truck packed with CIS peacekeepers exploded
on a remote-controlled land mine near the settlement of Pichora.
</P>
<P>
Shamba said it was Georgian commandos who carried out the
attack, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Despite a protocol on ceasefire reached in Gagra on May 25,
Georgian commandos are continuing their activities inside Abkhazia
in an attempt to destabilize the situation again, he added.
</P>
<P>
Shamba noted that certain forces in the Georgian leadership are
trying to thwart the planned meeting between the Georgian and
Abkhazian heads of state Eduard Shevardnadze and Vladislav
Ardzinba.
</P>
<P>
Several important documents are expected to be signed during
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
About 1,600 peacekeepers have been separating Georgian and
Abkhazian forces since June 1992 and are scheduled to leave on
July 31.
</P>
<P>
About 200 peacekeepers died and about 100 injured during their
stay in the troubled area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
