<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Enjoys Big Trade Surplus in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Union has enjoyed a
trade surplus of 2.3 billion ECUs (2.53 billion U.S. dollars) in
March bolstered by a strong export growth in the first quarter of
the year, Eurostat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The export growth in the January-March period was 18 percent
while that for 1997 was 12 percent, said the Luxembourg-based
statistical office of the European communities.
</P>
<P>
Germany, among the 15 EU states, posted the largest trade
surplus with 15.5 billion ECUs (17.1 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The bloc last year enjoyed a trade surplus of 50.2 billion ECUs
(55.4 billion dollars) with non-EU countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, March also witnessed a trade surplus of 7.7 billion
ECUs (8.49 billion dollars) for the 11 founding countries of the
European single currency, the euro, which will be launched in
January, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The surplus was boosted by an export growth of 17 percent in
the first three months of the year compared with 14 percent in the
same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The euro countries include Belgium, Germany, Spain, France,
Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Austria, Portugal and
Finland.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Denmark have opted out of the first wave for the
euro, while Greece and Sweden were judged by the EU not
economically ready to join for the time being. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
