<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Extend Directive to Fight Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission announced
on Monday it will extend and expand its directive on combating
money laundering in the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation union, is
considering amending the current anti-money laundering directive
to cover a wider prohibition, extending the directive to certain
non-financial activities and professions, improving cooperation
between financial intelligence units, an official of the
commission briefed the press Monday.
</P>
<P>
The commission hoped that it would come forward with a new
directive proposal late this year or early next year.
</P>
<P>
The current commission directive only obliges EU member states
to combat the laundering of the proceeds of drugs trafficking,
although nearly all the member states have already extended their
own legislation to cover the proceeds of crimes such as terrorism,
prostitution, fraud and illegal gaming.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials said that the move to extend and expand
the existing EU directive is designed to make anti-money
laundering more effective by extending the directive's obligations
to cover the activities and professions outside the financial
services sector such as auditors, legal professions, real estate
agents and casinos.
</P>
<P>
Such an extension will bring the EU rules in line with the
latest international recommendations and the Amsterdam European
Council's Action Plan to combat organized crimes, said the
official.
</P>
<P>
The commission admitted in a report that the number of
suspicious money laundering transaction reports rose in most EU
member states from 1994 to 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
