<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chengdu to Use BOT Method to Construct Waterworks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The City Government of Chengdu,
capital of southwest China's Sichuan Province, signed a draft
agreement on Sunday calling for a French company to construct a
new waterworks.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for the French-based Compagnie Generale Des
Eaux-New World Consortium to build the waterworks in line with
the BOT (build-operate-transfer). The project will be the first
urban public utility BOT project approved by the central
government.
</P>
<P>
The facility will consist of a water supply system with a daily
capacity of 400,000 tons, a water treatment plant with the same
capacity and a 27-km pipeline.
</P>
<P>
China has previously used the BOT method to construct railways
and expressways.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Set Up Committee for Restructuring Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian deputy prime
minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim Monday announced plans
to set up a joint public and private sector steering committee to
kick-start and expedite the restructuring of corporate debts.
</P>
<P>
"This committee will work with various groups of creditors
within an agreed framework to secure orderly and well-informed
decisions on whether, and on what terms a company, is worth
supporting," he told parliament while announcing a fiscal stimulus
and additional measures to restore economic growth.
</P>
<P>
According to Anwar, since the second half of 1997, the
performance of the corporate sector in Malaysia has deteriorated
significantly due to the regional economic and financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said a number of corporations, including large companies,
were facing serious financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring of debts is necessary to improve the
liquidity position of businesses that are still viable but
burdened by huge debts, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the objectives of restructuring corporate debts are to
minimize losses to creditors, shareholders and other stakeholders
and to prevent companies from facing liquidity problems.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the details of corporate debt restructuring, Anwar
said it would encompass four basic principles, which among others,
stipulate that creditor banks, despite their financial
difficulties, should continue to provide credit to companies.
</P>
<P>
"It is inappropriate for creditor banks to stop credit lines
and appoint receivers in haste," he said.
</P>
<P>
Losses should be jointly borne in a fair manner by creditors
according to specified categories, and decisions about a company's
future must be based on comprehensive information shared among all
parties, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that to accelerate debt restructuring, specific tax
incentives were being considered to encourage creditors to
participate in corporate debt restructuring.
</P>
<P>
"The government may also review the procedures related to the
foreign ownership and participation in some of the large
corporations to facilitate the restructuring process," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
