<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Banks Urged to Reschedule Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian deputy prime
minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim Monday urged banks to
reschedule their debts and not to put too much pressure on
companies to pay up.
</P>
<P>
"The government does not want creditor banks to put too much
pressure on companies to pay up," he told reporters after
announcing a fiscal stimulus and additional measures to restore
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"What is to be done is to get them (banks) together with the
private sector when encountering difficulty due to the decline in
share prices and the depreciation of the ringgit to reschedule
debts," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar announced in Parliament that Bank Negara (central bank)
will establish a special-purpose vehicle (SPV) to spearhead the
recapitalization of the banking sector, and the central bank would
 provide the initial capital and invite various multilateral
agencies to play an active role in the special agency.
</P>
<P>
He also announced plans to set up a joint public and private
sector steering committee to kick-start and expedite the
restructuring of corporate debts.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the restructuring of corporate debts is
necessary to ensure continued credit extension to generate
economic activities.
</P>
<P>
Debt restructuring will complement the role of Pengurusan
Danaharta Nasional Bhd, an asset management company established to
revive the non-performing loans (NPLs) of banking institutions,
and the SPV.
</P>
<P>
"We have now decided on the SPV for recapitalization of the
banking sector to ensure that all banks will be much more solid
and strong financially," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said banks have to take responsibility to carry on with
their business of lending and to stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
"It is not proper for the government to take all measures to
assist and recapitalize the banking sector and not ask the banks
to continue with their (lending) programs to productive sectors,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The recapitalization of the banking sector for 1998 and 1999
has been projected to be 16 billion ringgit (3.77 billion U.S.
dollars) to maintain the risk-weighted capital ratio at 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the government will consider applications for
foreign equity participation in any Malaysian company, without
prejudice, including telecommunications companies, and the
applications will be dealt with in accordance with set guidelines
and procedures.
</P>
<P>
Anwar also announced the revision of the country's gross
domestic product (GDP) growth to a negative rate of 1.0 percent to
2.0 percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's annual real GDP growth in the first quarter of the
year contracted by 1.8 percent, a negative GDP growth for the
first time in 13 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
