<HEADLINE> Ugandan Mayor Put Under House Arrest Before Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 10 (Xinhua) -- Nasser Sebaggala, Mayor of
Uganda's Kampala city, was put under house arrest by a federal
judge in Boston, the United States, pending trial on bank fraud
charges on a date yet to be set.
</P>
<P>
This decision dashed hopes that he would be allowed to return
home before trial.
</P>
<P>
During a detention hearing on Thursday, U.S. Magistrate Judge
Marianne Bowler placed Sebaggala under the custody of Edmund
Narine, a Boston resident, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The judge said the mayor will have to remain at Narine's house
until his trial. He can only leave the premises under "911
(emergency) situation."
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala was also made to deposit a cash bond of 50,000 U.S.
Dollars and an unsecured bond of 950,000 Dollars.
</P>
<P>
His defense lawyers said they plan to appeal the judge's
decision.
</P>
<P>
Paul Kelly, one of the two defense attorneys, told journalists
outside the court: "I am neither satisfied nor pleased with the
verdict...nevertheless, I respect the judge's decision. We will
definitely appeal the judge's decision and we will ask the
district judge to review the conditions and allow Mr. Sebaggala
to return to Kampala and perform his duties as Mayor."
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala, however, told his Kampala supporters in a call
Thursday that he is innocent and is confident that he will return
home any time.
</P>
<P>
Sebaggala was arrested on June 13 in New York for allegedly
making false customs declaration and depositing altered checks in
a U.S. bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
