<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Firm On Shrimp Farming Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
has refused to budge over a ban on inland shrimp farming in
freshwater areas nationwide despite protests by farm operators.
</P>
<P>
The government will go ahead with the resolution of the
National Environment Board (NEB), which has been under scrutiny
for the last three months, a TV report Monday quoted Chuan as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Chuan was commenting on a plan by inland shrimp farmers in 13
provinces, who form the Black Tiger Shrimp Farmers' Club, to rally
near the parliament Tuesday to force the government to rescind the
ban.
</P>
<P>
The Thai cabinet last week endorsed the NEB's resolution to
impose the ban, to be enforced 120 days after the prime minister
issues a decree to implement the ban. It is not clear when Chuan
will issue the decree.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said that although he had sympathy for inland shrimp
farmers, he would not allow shrimp farming to harm the
environment.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists say inland shrimp farming occupies large
amounts of limited arable land and erodes the soil with salt water
carried over from the sea.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said he would ask the Science Ministry to explain to the
public the need to ban inland shrimp farming.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision to ban inland shrimp farming has
prompted an outcry from shrimp farmers nationwide. Several rallies
have been held in protest against the decision. The farmers' club
said the farmers would continue to hold rallies until the
government rescinds the ban or extends the 120-day grace period to
a year or 18 months.
</P>
<P>
But the ban has won the support of many non-governmental
organizations and people who insist that the environment should
not be sacrificed for economic benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
