<HEADLINE> Lawmaker Dismissed for Malfeasance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior lawmaker in north China's
Hebei Province has been dismissed from his post and incarcerated
for gambling and accepting bribes.
</P>
<P>
The Central Commission for Discipline Inspection of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) issued a circular today stating
that Jiang Dianwu, former deputy director of the Hebei People's
Congress Standing Committee, was also expelled from the CPC.
</P>
<P>
Jiang was found guilty of authorizing the establishment of a
Hebei gambling house known as "Bocai", and accepting bribes of
40,000 Hong Kong dollars in cash and goods valued at 11,000 yuan
during the process. The circular points out that gambling in China
is prohibited by law.
</P>
<P>
The former official also solicited 150,000 yuan of bribes from
a shareholder in the Yanzhao Woolen Mill in Hebei.
</P>
<P>
In a related case, a state-run enterprise complied with Jiang's
request to allocate 25,000 yuan in public funds for his wife,
daughter, son-in-law, daughter-in-law and unnamed individuals to
travel to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The circular urged all Party members, especially officials, to
learn from Jiang's case.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's misdeeds resulted from his "lack of political concepts
and discipline," according to the circular.  
</P>
