<HEADLINE> Nigeria Feels Impact of Asian Crises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian companies, especially
those in the manufacturing sector, are now paying dearly for the
economic crises that have been rocking most Southeast Asian
countries in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The Business Concord Monday quoted a leading retail company
chairman as saying all manner of goods from that region were now
being dumped in Nigeria and sold at ridiculous prices.
</P>
<P>
Bassey Ndiokho, chairman and chief executive of UAC of Nigeria
Plc, noted that the situation had brought intense competition
against locally made goods whose prices are not quite
competitive.
</P>
<P>
He did not go further on how the financial crises in Southeast
Asia have affected the Nigerian economy.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that as a matter of fact, the first half of
this year had turned out to be worse than last year for almost
all sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a number of factors had combined to make the
first half year a tough and rough period for Nigerian
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
These included the significant fall of oil prices in the world
market, the energy crises within the country and the image
problems of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, he believed strongly that the second half of this
year would be much better as the steps which are being taken by
the present administration and are opening the way for some world
leaders to hold talks with Nigeria would go a long way in
improving the situation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
