<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-IMF Official to Govern Tanzania's Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Daudi Ballali, a veteran
Tanzanian official assigned to work at the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) for 21 years has been appointed the new Governor of
the Bank of Tanzania (BOT), an official statement said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with an order by President Benjamin Mkapa,
Ballali, now personnel assistant to the President on Economic
Affairs, will replace Idris Rashid, whose contract expires
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ballali, 56, has been in financial institutions since late
1960s when he joined the BOT as an economist, and rose to the
position of Director of Research and Secretary to the Board
before leaving in 1976 to work for the IMF.
</P>
<P>
In his 21-year experience at the IMF, Ballali rose through the
ranks to become Deputy Division Chief in 1986, a position he held
until last year when he become an assistant to President Mkapa.
</P>
<P>
While at IMF, Ballali helped African countries such as Ghana
and Lesotho develop and implement successful economic reform
programs supported by the fund.
</P>
<P>
Between 1986 and 1997 he headed many IMF missions to Africa
such as Swaziland, Botswana, Kenya, Ethiopia, South Africa,
Sierra Leone and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
He also supervised and monitored the implementation of
economic reform programs in some of those countries on behalf of
the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Born on August 17, 1942 at Mufindi, Iringa Region and married
with two children, Ballali was educated at Tosamaganga Secondary
School before going to the United States where he received his
university education, earning a Bachelor in Economics from Howard
University in 1965 and a Master in Economics in 1967 from the
Catholic University of America.  
</P>
</TEXT>
