<HEADLINE> China to Step up Crack Down on Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
announced today that a national police force will be established
to intensify the crack down on rampant smuggling in China.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the announcement while meeting delegates to a
national anti-smuggling work conference that opened here today.
</P>
<P>
The special force will operate under the joint guidance of
customs administrations and public security departments.
</P>
<P>
Reforming and improving the anti-smuggling system will provide
a "timely and highly effective" means for the crack down on
smuggling, said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that resolute determination, prompt response,
effective measures and severe punishment will help deliver a
telling blow against rampant smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that concentrated efforts will be devoted to
solving major smuggling cases "regardless of institutions or
individuals involved."
</P>
<P>
He instructed all Party and governmental offices,
law-enforcement agencies and judiciary departments to carefully
investigate affiliated companies for the existence of smuggling
activities.
</P>
<P>
Jiang's remarks came in response to the fact that certain
officials from government departments have further complicated the
problem by directly participating in or shielding smuggling
activities.
</P>
<P>
Customs officers directly participating in or shielding
criminal acts will be investigated and punished severely, said
Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Also meeting the delegates were Premier Zhu Rongji, Wei
Jianxing, a Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and secretary
of the CPC Central Commission for Discipline Inspection, and
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing. 
</P>
