<HEADLINE> Protestant Parade Go Ahead Amid Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The traditional march of Northern
Ireland's Protestant residents in Belfast, known as the Orange
Parade, passed off peacefully Monday morning amid tensions created
by a bomb alert and a murder one day ago.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 marchers walked in silence along the Ormeau Road,
which passes through Belfast's Catholic neighborhood, while
hundreds of other Protestants watched along the route, reported
BBC TV news.
</P>
<P>
The planed parade had caused violence and tensions lately
between Belfast's Protestant and Catholic residents, with the
Catholics regarding it as a provocative move.
</P>
<P>
The march finally took place after local Catholic residents
agreed to stage only a "dignified" silent protest to the parade.
</P>
<P>
The march went ahead only 24 hours after a horrorable attack in
which three Catholic children in deep sleep were burnt to death.
</P>
<P>
The killings sent shock waves through both communities in the
bitterly divided British-ruled province and cast a shadow over
hopes of stability in the wake of a peace deal hammered out by
rival politicians in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
