<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The number of tourists visiting Lebanon in the first
five months this year reached 187,775, up 11.44 percent from the
same period last year, the Arabic-language Alshark Alawsat
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In April alone, 52,279 tourists visited the country, nearly
accounting for 27.8 percent of total in first five months.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisian textile exports rose to 2.7 billion
U.S. dollars in 1997 from 1.2 billion dollars in 1991, an increase
of 14.2 percent, according to the latest figures from Trade
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon has 313,000 vacant residential and
non-residential houses and apartments while thousands of Lebanese
can not afford to buy homes, the government's Central Statistics
Office said in its latest report.
</P>
<P>
The report was compiled after an 18-month census by the office.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Ciments Libanais, Lebanon's biggest cement company,
said its 1997 net profit fell to 1.74 million dollars, a decrease
of 82.3 percent from 9.99 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The fall was attributed to a provision of 8 million dollars for
the depreciation of the old kilns and the spare parts.
</P>
<P>
The company's net profit in 1996 was 9.99 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan and Egypt agreed Monday to launch an electric
grid in October that connects the two countries, Jordan's official
news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
The grid will be part of a regional grid that is also to link
Syria, Lebanon, Iraq and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The whole project will be completed by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made Monday during the talks between Jordanian
Minister of Energy and Mineral Resources Mohammed Saleh Hourani
and officials from the Egyptian Embassy in Jordan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
