<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal's Trade Deficit Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's total foreign trade
dropped slightly in the first nine months of the 1997/98 fiscal
year ending mid-July, but the deficit narrowed by 10.5 percent,
the Finance Ministry says.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign trade during the period dropped by 0.3
compared with the year-ago level, and amounted to 85.638 billion
rupees (1.3 billion U.S. dollars), the ministry says in its latest
Economic Survey.
</P>
<P>
But the total trade deficit declined by 10.5 percent to 46.727
billion rupees (700 million dollars) with export up 15.7 percent
and import down 4.1 percent, the survey notes.
</P>
<P>
"Due to the decline in trade deficit, it seems that the
country's external trade is gradually orienting toward
improvement," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Nepal's trade with India rose by 9.1 percent to 25.62 billion
rupees (400 million dollars) while the deficit with that country
fell by 13.2 percent to 13.294 billion rupees (200 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Nepal's trade with other countries dropped by 3.8 percent to
60.018 billion rupees (900 million dollars) and the deficit fell
by 9.4 percent. Of the exports to them, woolen carpets accounted
for 48.4 percent, ready-made garments 41.6 percent and pulses 6.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the same period last year, export of ready-made
garments and pulses was growing as usual but that of woolen
carpets was declining, the report says.
</P>
<P>
The report says that at the end of the 1996/97 fiscal year,
Nepal's foreign currency reserves stood at 48.541 billion rupees
(700 million dollars) and rose by 25.1 percent by mid-April 1998
to 60.721 billion rupees (920 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The ministry in its report also urges efforts to promote the
export-oriented industries so as to reduce the huge trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
In view of the wide ratio of the current account deficit to
gross domestic product (GDP), foreign savings has to be increased
to cover the gap, it says. "Therefore, it is imperative to control
increasing budget deficit in order to improve current account
deficit by increasing the ratio of internal savings over the
investment."
</P>
<P>
And "in order to make balance of payments surplus sustainable,
a strong need has arisen to take firm measures to attract maximum
amount of direct foreign investment in the economy which will
positively contribute to the economic development of the country,"
the report says.
</P>
<P>
"It is all the more important in the context of the declining
trade in the official capital flow in the future," it says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
