<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kenyan Banks Woo Customers with New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Major banks in Kenya have
responded to the volatile money market by introducing innovative
products to increase the number of account holders and expand
their lending business.
</P>
<P>
Standard Chartered Bank, in partnership with Microsoft, is
offering its account holders an opportunity to own a home
computer system on easy credit terms.
</P>
<P>
The package includes access to the Internet at subsidized
rates, as well as computer training.
</P>
<P>
"We are providing finance to enable those interested in access
to computer technology to do so," the bank's product manager
Lerionoka Tiampati was quoted by Monday's East African weekly as
saying.
</P>
<P>
With an initial deposit of 20 percent of the value of the
package (about 40,000 Shillings or some 667 U.S. Dollars), the
bank provides instant unsecured credit repayable in 24 months at
instalments of less than 10,000 Shillings (167 Dollars) monthly.
</P>
<P>
Barclays Bank of Kenya has launched an aggressive media
campaign to promote its Barclayloan scheme, which offers account
holders quick access to funds with a flexible repayment schedule.
</P>
<P>
It enables account holders to obtain unsecured funds of
between 10,000 Shillings and 500,000 Shillings (8,333 Dollars) to
the purchase of specific items including motor vehicles, home
furnishings and appliances, payment of medical, holiday and
travel expense, purchase of shares or payment of taxes.
</P>
<P>
The maximum repayment period for a Barclayloan to purchase a
car is 60 months, while loans for buying furniture and home
appliances can be repaid in 24 months.
</P>
<P>
However, to qualify for a Barclayloan, proof of ownership of a
home, telephone and a credit card is required, in addition to a
loanee having been an account holder with the bank for at least
six months.
</P>
<P>
Barclays Bank managing director Gareth George recently said
the bank is reviewing its lending policies to allow more
applicants access to this Barclayloan scheme.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of unsecured credit facilities by commercial
banks in Kenya is in keeping with a worldwide trend in which
financial bodies are gradually moving from collateral-based
lending to loans based on availability of project or a borrower's
ability to pay, experts say.
</P>
<P>
A number of other Kenyan banks, like the Cooperation Bank,
Kenya Commercial Bank and National Bank of Kenya, also run
specialized credit schemes.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Commercial Bank (KCB) has a University Graduate Loan
Scheme, credit schemes targeting women groups and the informal
sector and concessionary credit lines for coffee and tea farmers
for the purchase of farm machinery and inputs.
</P>
<P>
KCB's Public Relations Officer Kefa Bosire said the
non-collateral credit schemes have enabled the bank to expand its
revenue base and diversify its product line.
</P>
<P>
Customers have been shunning conventional bank loans due to
the prevailing high interest rates, currently pegged at between
25-30 percent, and most savers do not meet collateral demanded by
banks.
</P>
<P>
There are 53 commercial banks and 16 non-bank financial
institutions in the east African country, according to the
Central Bank of Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Insurers Issue Warning on Bank Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's insurance industry has
warned that it might cease covering some areas of banking if
immediate measures were not taken to stern the recent wave of
armed raids on banks in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
Bank robberies have been rampant in Kenya recently with four
banks in Nairobi and Mombasa, the largest two cities in Kenya,
having been raided since last month.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Kenya Insurers (AKI) said that if the
robberies continued, the insurance companies may be forced to
avoid high risk aspects of banking.
</P>
<P>
"Our concern stems from the fact that since all banks are
insured for cash in transit and money on the premises, it is the
insurers who absorb the losses in case of robberies," Monday's
East African weekly quoted an AKI statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
"This means an unnecessary diversion of resources from
productive sectors to non-productive activities," said the
statement issued last week.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Bankers Association (KBA), in response, said the
banks were equally concerned about the robberies and had set up a
committee which works closely with the Central Bank of Kenya's
Anti-Fraud Squad.
</P>
<P>
"This is not an issue for the banking industry alone but a
reflection of the general rate of crime and insecurity in the
country," said KBA.
</P>
<P>
Among immediate measures the insurance industry has
recommended for banks is reduction of cash held by tellers at any
given time, as well as the total amount held in bank's vaults.
</P>
<P>
"The objective is to minimize the amounts of money stolen in
the event of a robbery," said Tom Aciando, a senior official with
American Life Insurance Company.
</P>
<P>
Banking sources said the requirement had already been
implemented, with tellers not holding more than 1.2 million
Shillings (20,000 U.S. Dollars) at any one time.
</P>
<P>
Requirements that banks step up their internal security and
surveillance system are also said to have been effected by most
banks, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said the surveillance cameras video-taped the
entire robbery at the Mashareq Bank early this month in which
500,000 Shillings (8,333 Dollars) was stolen, providing vital
clues to police.
</P>
<P>
However, the KBA said banks cannot adequately control the
amount of cash in their vaults due to the daily needs by
supermarkets and others doing cash withdrawals for purpose of
stock purchases or customers change.
</P>
<P>
Insurers are also considering increasing premiums and excess
charges in case of a theft or loss. The premiums rates vary from
0.01 percent to three percent of the annual cash carriage.
</P>
<P>
Banking sources hinted last week that a hike in premiums will
be passed on to customers and could further inflate the already
high banking service charges.
</P>
<P>
The new demands by the insurance industry are likely to
adversely affect small banks, which lack enough resources to
effect the recommended security measures.
</P>
<P>
There are 53 registered banking institutions in Kenya, 47 of
which are small banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
