<HEADLINE> Museveni Sworn in as Chairperson of NRM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has been sworn in as chairperson of Uganda's ruling National
Resistance Movement (NRM) at its national conference which began
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Museveni, who was re-elected the boss of the NRM without any
opposition from a total of some 1,600 delegates at the
International Conference Center at 9:00 a.m. (0600GMT), made
several commitments in his 40-minute speech after the swearing-in
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that in his five-year term as the chairperson, the
Movement would continue to stress decentralization, Universal
Primary Education (UPE) as it had done.
</P>
<P>
To receive education is the best way to empower youths and
women in rural areas, he said. It is education which can improve
the quality of Ugandans.
</P>
<P>
The NRM would continue to commit itself to bringing more
democracy to Uganda, modernizing the society, liberalizing the
economy, stabilizing the foreign exchange rate, eliminating
poverty and reconciliating with those against the government, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said he would use all his energy for the progress of the
Movement.
</P>
<P>
At Monday's conference, Moses Kigongo from the Buganda Region
was elected the vice chairperson of the NRM.
</P>
<P>
The national congress of the NRM convenes every five years. It
is mainly participated by NRM's local council leaders, members of
parliament, representatives from some interest groups.
</P>
<P>
The NRM was formed in June 1981 and has been Uganda's ruling
party since it took power in January 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
