<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Concerned About Hashimoto's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC), the
executive body of the 15-nation European Union, voiced concern
over the announced resignation of Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A commission spokesman said the EC was concerned about the
future of economic reforms the Japanese government had pledged.
</P>
<P>
The election results showed the Japanese people wanted further
measures to tackle its economic slump, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the EC would closely follow the development around
Hashimoto's resignation.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto resigned on Monday as president of the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) and hence Japanese prime minister after the
party suffered a devastating setback in the upper house poll on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
LDP won only 44 seats in the 126-seat upper house, falling far
short of the 69 seats they needed to regain a majority in the
chamber, which it lost in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto led the LDP since September 1995 and became prime
minister from January 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
