<HEADLINE> China Expresses Opposition to U.S. Anti-China Resolutions (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang
Guoqiang said today that China strongly resents and is resolutely
opposed to recent anti-China resolutions adopted by the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
Tang made the remark in response to a question concerning two
recent resolutions passed by the U.S. senate.
</P>
<P>
On July 10, the U.S. Senate passed a resolution tabled by
Senator Trent Lott, Republican majority leader of the Senate,
requiring the Clinton administration to continue arms sales to
Taiwan and urging the U.S. government to press China not to use
force in the reunification effort.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the Senate also passed a resolution
U.S. Senator Jesse Holms tabled supporting Taiwan's entry into the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Tang reiterated that the Taiwan issue is the most important and
sensative aspect in Sino-U.S. relations. "The key to ensuring the
healthy and stable growth of Sino-U.S. ties lies in properly
handling the Taiwan issue in accordance with the principle set
forth in the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques," said Tang.
</P>
<P>
Tang said the U.S. government clearly committed itself to
observing the "One China Policy", as well as the principles
outlined in the three communiques.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. government has clearly pledged it will not
support the concepts of 'Two Chinas' or 'One China, One Taiwan,"
as well as Taiwan independence and Taiwan's entry into any
international organizations composed by sovereign countries,"
according to Tang.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. side has also promised to resolve issues related to
arms sales to Taiwan in accordance with the August 17 Sino-U.S.
Communique.
</P>
<P>
"We firmly believe the U.S. side should strictly observe all
the above principles and implement all related commitments," he
stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Expresses Opposition to U.S. Anti-China Resolutions (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The basic policy of the Chinese government on the Taiwan issue
is to peacefully reunify China and observe the concept of "one
country, two systems", according to Tang.
</P>
<P>
"The reunification of China's is purely China's internal affair
and no foreign interference will be allowed."
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that only sovereign states can join the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank, both of which
operate under the auspices of the United Nations. "Taiwan is an
integral part of and as such is not qualified to join the two
organizations," said Tang.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reiterated that the development of the
Sino-U.S. relationship is in the fundamental interests of the two
countries and represents the common aspirations of the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
The joint efforts of the two sides led to the recent highly
successful visit to China by President Clinton, said Tang, adding
that the momentum for improving and developing bilateral relations
resulted from extensive efforts which are well worth cherishing.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that attempts by some U.S. congressmen to promote
anti-China resolutions are "doomed to failure". He stressed that
such attempts will simply obstruct continuing improvements and the
development of Sino-U.S. relations and thus run counter to
historic trends.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely hope the U.S. Congress will proceed in the
fundamental interests of the two countries and their people and
will play a positive rather than a negative role in the bilateral
relationship.
</P>
<P>
"We also hope the U.S. government will adopt effective measures
to remove obstacles and prevent the Congress from adopting
related resolutions in order to ensure the bilateral relationship
remains undamaged," said Tang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
