<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Deport 109 Boat People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Interior Minister Dinos
Michaelides announced Monday that Cyprus has decided to deport 109
illegal Arab and African immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Michaelides told reporters here that the deportation procedures
would be soon completed for these immigrants, who illegally
entered Cyprus by a boat last month.
</P>
<P>
He said the boat people would be returned to their home
countries despite their wish to remain in Cyprus. He added that
the domestic and international laws should be implemented.
</P>
<P>
These illegal immigrants camed from countries including the
Democratic Republic of Congo, Egypt, Iraq, Lebanon, Libya,
Nigeria, Sierra Leone and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
They reportedly left Tripoli of Lebanon on June 18 on a small
Syrian-flagged fishing boat after paying as much as 5,000 U.S.
dollars each to go to either Greece or Italy.
</P>
<P>
Without food or fresh water, the immigrants were found 11 days
later by a Ukrainian-flagged commercial vessel, which towed it to
Cyprus on June 29.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government accommodated the immigrants at a hotel
in the southern coastal town of Limassol. About 20 policemen have
been assigned to guard them while the authority conducted an
investigation and issued new travel documents for them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
