<HEADLINE> UN Organ to Help Jordan in WTO Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has adopted a U.N. technical
assistance project that will help the country in the accession
talks with the World Trade Organization (WTO), a press release
issued here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the release issued by the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), the 300,000 U.S. dollar UNDP project
was approved by Jordan's Ministry of Planning.
</P>
<P>
The project was aimed at increasing Jordan's competitiveness in
its gradual integration into the global market, especially in its
preparation for the upcoming WTO accession negotiations later this
month.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, experts from the Geneva-based
U.N. Conference on Trade and Development will help Jordan's
negotiators develop technical and mediation skills in talks with
WTO representatives. This will prepare the ground for Jordan's
final integration into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Officials at Jordan's Ministry of Trade, Commerce and Supply
who will be directly involved in the entry talks, will receive
training on bilateral and multilateral trade negotiations and on
function of the WTO.
</P>
<P>
A team of high-level international consultants will also be
recruited to assist in the preparation for the negotiations, the
release said.
</P>
<P>
The project is part of the UNDP's efforts to boost Jordan
capacity to integrate itself into the global economy and increase
its performance in a highly competitive environment, especially in
the fields of investment and trade, the release added.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP believed that the stringent rules in the WTO
agreements on trade of goods and services and the enforcement of
intellectual property rights will pose grave challenges for Jordan
on its bid to join the 132-member WTO.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Trade, Commerce and Supply Hani Mulqi said in May
that Jordan expected to join the WTO by mid-1999 after it
introduces a new package of economic regulations.
</P>
<P>
Jordan used to rely on regional trade, and intellectual
property rights are reportedly not well respected in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
