<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indian Population Clock Ticking Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- India's population reached
979,860,411 at 7 a.m. Sunday, moving close to the 1 billion mark
and signalizing that the South Asian country might relegate China
to second place as the most populous country in the world just in
a few decades.
</P>
<P>
With some 30 people born every minute and 43,000 each day on an
average, the population in India is projected to reach 1,264
million by 2016, thus surpassing China's present population of 1.2
billion, the Press Trust of India said Sunday, quoting Executive
Director of the Population Foundation of India K. Srinivasan.
</P>
<P>
With only 2.4 percent of the land area but 16 percent of the
population in the world, this mass of humanity in India has kept
putting increasing pressure on its infrastructure, economy,
environment, education, primary health care and nutrition.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that India formulated an official population
policy as early as in 1952, its population went up to 846 million
in 1991 from 345 million at the time of independence in 1947.
</P>
<P>
The latest 100 million were added in less than six years while
it took 42 years for the population to add 100 million before
independence.
</P>
<P>
India's population is not only large but has also been
maintaining unacceptably high rates of growth.
</P>
<P>
The main reason is that the family planning programs are not
implemented qualitatively and, secondly, it is because there are
no programs for educating women in many states.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, there is no political commitment in many states,
resulting in the disparity in the success of the schemes,
Srinivasan said.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported about the failure in program
implementation and about what is called "plans without planning."
</P>
<P>
The Indian Express daily reported Sunday that a high-profile
group of eminent scientists and demographers headed by noted
scientist M. S. Swaminathan chalked out five years ago what was to
be the "definitive" population policy for the next few decades.
</P>
<P>
Four successive governments have mulled over the draft,
moderated and modified it, yet it is still a long way to go for a
comprehensive population policy to be adopted.
</P>
<P>
The National Agenda for Governance announced last March by the
ruling Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) speaks of a "suitable and
judicious mix of incentives and disincentives for population
control."
</P>
<P>
However, the experience of health professionals in the field is
that any scheme involving disincentives runs into a slew of
problems, primarily because the line dividing what is termed a
"disincentive" and outright coercion is often blurred.
</P>
<P>
The major obstacle to the successful implementation of family
planning and welfare schemes is the lack of funding.
</P>
<P>
In the 8th five-year plan from 1992 to 1997, the Department of
Family Welfare received some 70 billion rupees (1.85 billion U.S.
dollars) as against 65 billion rupees (1.76 billion dollars) in
the 7th five-year plan.
</P>
<P>
Because the resources have been not able to cover even the
costs of maintaining the current programs, the department has not
been able to increase the range of contraceptive use in the
programs, or to strengthen the supporting reproductive and child
health systems, according to a latest government report on family
welfare programs.
</P>
<P>
However, the programs have attracted more external assistance
and last Saturday the United Nations Population Fund announced 100
million U.S. dollars in support of India's population and
development programs.
</P>
<P>
The government has made some progress in family and welfare
programs, the report said. Infant mortality rate was brought down
from 146 in 1951-61 to 72 in 1996 per 1,000 live births and crude
death rate fell from 22.8 to nine per 1,000 in the same period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
