<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Hopes Japan Not to Change Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia believes Tokyo's policy
toward Moscow will not change with Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto's resignation, a Russian official said.
</P>
<P>
The ranking official with the Russian Foreign Ministry was
quoted by an Itar-Tass news agency report as saying Monday that
Moscow regards Hashimoto's step down as Japan's internal affair.
</P>
<P>
The decision to resign is his personal step made in keeping
with traditions of Japanese politics, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese premier officially announced his decision earlier
in the day, and his resignation had already been approved at a
meeting of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) leadership.
</P>
<P>
As the LDP remains in power, the Russian diplomat said, Russia
wants to see its relations with Japan further developed along the
same line which the Hashimoto administration has been following.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko arrived Monday in Tokyo on a two-day official visit
designed to help boost bilateral trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The visit immediately followed the Japanese ruling party's
crushing defeat in the Sunday election of the House of
Councillors, or the upper house of parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
