<HEADLINE> Singapore Stocks Take Hammering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Stocks took a
hammering Monday as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index
(STII) lost 37.16 points to close at 1,053.19.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said share prices were hammered down by the resignation
of Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto who took the move for
his responsibility for the crippling defeat of his ruling Liberal
Democratic Party in Upper House elections.
</P>
<P>
His resignation unsettled the regional markets, they said.
</P>
<P>
Dealers also said that investors were also spooked by a fear of
corporate insolvencies in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
They quoted news report as saying that Malaysia's Renong unit
Times Telecommunication is set to seek court protection from
creditors this week.
</P>
<P>
This has underscored the growing problems of corporate
insolvency in Malaysia's private sector, they said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover totaled 122.64 million shares valued at 221.53 million
Singapore dollars (128.35 million U.S. dollars). Losers
outstripped gainers by 270 to 42 while 279 stocks remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
DBS Land, a major developer, was the most active stock as it
registered a turnover of 5.76 million units. MBF Cap had 5.47
million counters done. ST ENGG was next with 5.32 million shares
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Genting topped gainers of the day as it edged up 14 cents to
end at 3.24 Singapore dollars. Hind Ho gained eight cents to
finish at 1.06 Singapore dollars. Nat Broad inched up by 8 cents
to close at 0.78 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, YHS was the biggest loser as it lost 46 cents
to finish at 4.44 Singapore dollars. UOB F shed 45 cents to 5.10
Singapore dollars. Chem. Ind. lost 30 cents to 1.80 Singapore
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
