<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Population to Reach 318 Million by 2050 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
here Monday urged the people to continue practicing birth control
as the country's population is expected to reach 318 million by
the year 2050.
</P>
<P>
"We need to sustain the success of our family planning program
because failing to do so will result in impacts that will be felt
in the future," the president told a gathering during the
observance of World Population Day.
</P>
<P>
Habibie pledged that the government will continue to give
priority to the family planning program, which encourages each
couple to have only two children.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government introduced the family planning
program in the early 1970s to check population growth and help the
people increase their prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia now has more than 200 million people, making it the
fourth most populous nation in the world" after India, India and
the United States, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president said that if the country successfully carries out
its birth control program, Indonesia would lower its rank to sixth
by 2050.
</P>
<P>
By then, India would be the most populous country with about
1.53 billion people, followed by China (1.51 billion), Pakistan
(357 million), the United States (348 million), Nigeria (339
million) and Indonesia (318 million).
</P>
<P>
"Our success in the family planning program must also be
followed by successes in improving the people's quality of life
and in distributing the population more evenly," Habibie added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
