<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A source from the Mozambican
Ministry of Industry, Commerce and Tourism said Mozambique and
South Africa will try their best to export maize to the Southern
Africa Development Community (SADC) countries to meet their
needs.
</P>
<P>
The source revealed this here Sunday, according to Monday's
Noticias newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The source who required anonymity said the maize production in
southern African region for the 1997/98 agricultural year, is
estimated to be 2.6 million to 3.5 million tons short of
expectation, and maize shortage is possible in Malawi, Zambia and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique will have 115,000 tons of maize in stock for export
to Malawi and Zambia which are over 400,000 tons short of need.
</P>
<P>
The ministry source noted that South Africa will try to
restrict its maize export to the places outside the southern
African region so as to satisfy the regional need. 
