<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Announces Budget Deficit for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim Monday announced that there would be a
budget deficit of about 10.0 billion ringgit (2.358 billion U.S.
dollars) for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The deficit in the Federal Government budget is a result of an
additional allocation of about 7.0 billion ringgit (1.65 billion
dollars) for development expenditure in 1998, Anwar, who is also
finance minister, said when unveiling fiscal stimulus and
additional measures to revive the economy in Parliament here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said the bulk of the additional allocation would be
distributed to various projects involving agriculture, housing,
education, infrastructure and public facilities, industrial
development, rural development, health, and poverty eradication.
</P>
<P>
In outlining the criteria for projects to qualify for the
additional allocation, Anwar said they include projects that will
not cause a decline in reserves or outflow of liquidity, enable
import substitution and increase exports of goods and services and
are capable of generating demand for domestic goods and services.
</P>
<P>
They should also increase efficiency and national
competitiveness, result in the output of goods and services with a
short gestation period, and ensure that the social safety net is
in place, he said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the budget deficit would be financed from domestic
sources, international institutions as well as through
international market loans,
</P>
<P>
He said the international institutions from which funds would
be tapped include the World Bank, Asian Development Bank and
Islamic Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
Anwar also said that non-performing loans in the banking
system, on a net basis, has risen to 8.5 percent at the end of May
compared with 4.7 percent at the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
"If the conditions under the worst case scenario materializes,
the projected recapitalization required for the banking system for
1998 and 1999 will be 16.0 billion ringgit (3.773 billion dollars)
in order to maintain the risk-weighted capital ratio of nine
percent," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
