<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia, SACU Sign Trade Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Zambia and the South African
Customs Union (SACU) will sign a trade agreement Monday in South
Africa, opening the latter's market to many Zambian commodities
on favorable conditions.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving here on Sunday for Pretoria, capital of South
Africa, to sign the agreement, Zambian Commerce, Trade and
Industry Minister Enock Kavindele said the occasion is important
for Zambia because it will boost its export to the SACU member
countries, to South Africa in particular, which has maintained a
strict import code, according to Zambia Daily Mail Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement to be signed, Zambian beef, wooden doors,
window frames, cement, metal cables, jewellery, clothes, sugar,
milk, soap, beer and vegetables will enjoy zero duty on the SACU
market.
</P>
<P>
Kavindele said the agreement, reached after protracted
negotiations, has challenged Zambian farmers and business
community to meet the quotas to be given under it.
</P>
<P>
"There has been an outcry from the Zambian business community
for us to level the playing field with their South African
compatriots, here is an opportunity for them to prove their worth
and I do not think they will fail to measure up to the
challenge," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement will allow most goods to enter South
African market duty free although some of them will attract
customs but at a reduced rate.
</P>
<P>
The highest rate will be at 20 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to push for larger quotas for our sugar and milk and
hope Zambian entrepreneurs will be able to maintain export
standards so that our products can compete favorably," Kavindele
said.
</P>
<P>
In the past Zambian business sector complained about
unbalanced trade with SACU which comprises South Africa,
Botswana, Swaziland, Namibia and Lesotho. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
