<HEADLINE> South African Property World's Cheapest: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The occupancy costs of
office and industrial property in South Africa are still the
lowest in the world, property sources have said.
</P>
<P>
According to London-based Healey and Baker, an associate of
the local group Marriot Property Services, Tokyo of Japan remains
the most expensive city in the world with occupancy costs (rental
and other costs) averaging 1,307 U.S. dollars square meter a year
followed by London, the next most expensive location at 1,051
Dollars square meter a year.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, Cape Town, the legislative capital of South
Africa, has average occupancy costs at 117 Rand (18.5 U.S.
Dollars) square meter a year, local daily the Citizen reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tony Bales, director of Marriot Property Services, said South
Africa outperformed all other regions with office rental growth
in 1996 and has done so again 1997 with growth of 14.7 percent.
The country was likely to perform well this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Tokyo also remains the world's most
expensive industrial location with occupancy costs of 397 U.S.
Dollars square meter a year while Singapore is also costly at 308
Dollars annually a square meter.
</P>
<P>
London has the highest cost in Europe at 217 U.S. Dollars a
square meter a year for the major airport locations, with Moscow
of Russia the second most expensive location at 180 U.S. Dollars
per square meter.
</P>
<P>
Cape Town at 41 U.S. Dollars sq m a year and the port city of
Durban in east South Africa at 37 Dollars sq m a year are the
cheapest in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heroin Worth 26M U.S. Dollars Seized in Auckland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Customs officers
seized a heroin shipment worth a record 26 million U.S. dollars at
Auckland International Airport last Thursday, the Customs Service
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The heroin came from Thailand and was believed to have been
headed for Australia.
</P>
<P>
Customs Service investigations manager Phil Chitty said Monday
that it was the highest value ever drugs haul in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
He said that the previous highest was 10.4 million U.S. dollars
worth of cocaine seized from a ship in Auckland about 10 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
Chitty said the heroin arrived on an aircraft from Bangkok late
 Thursday morning and Customs officers were waiting to pounce.
</P>
<P>
"Customs and police drug investigators conducted a controlled
delivery of the consignment, and this resulted in the arrest of
two Vietnamese males late Friday afternoon, after an attempt had
been made to send the consignment on to Australia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chitty disclosed that the operation was a "direct outcome of
information" provided by New Zealand Customs and police officers
based permanently at the New Zealand Embassy in Bangkok. 
</P>
</TEXT>
