<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka's Revenue Registers 8 Pct Shortfall in 97-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's revenue earnings stood
at 155.8 billion taka (3.32 billion U.S. dollars), about eight
percent less than the target fixed for the 1997-98 fiscal year
which ended June 30 this year, The Financial Express daily
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Though the country's revenue earnings registered 8 percent
shortfall, it was still 12.97 billion taka (2.76 billion dollars)
more or 10.37 percent higher than the amount earned in the
previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Tax revenue during the 1997-98 fiscal year amounted to 138
billion taka (2.94 billion dollars) against the target of 150
billion taka (3.2 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The overall shortfall in revenue earnings forced the government
to cut the size of the annual development program by 6 billion
taka (128 million dollars) in the revised 1997-98 fiscal year
budget from the original size of 128 billion taka (2.72 billion
dollars) program.
</P>
<P>
The reasons for the shortfall in the revenue earnings were
attributed to a big fall in imports, congestion at Chittagong port
and large scale smuggling of foreign goods into the country,
officials concerned were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Revenue collected from imports stood at 80.5 billion taka (1.71
billion dollars), 6.6 billion taka (140 million dollars) less than
the target, due to the import declined substantially.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in the industrial production also affected the
revenue income in domestic sector, from which the revenue
collected stood at only 36 billion taka (766 million dollars)
against the target of 39.4 billion taka (838 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Earnings from income tax also declined by two billion taka
(42.6 million dollars) in the last fiscal year against the target
of 21.5 billion (45.7 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Strives to Eradicate Polio by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
vowed Monday to focus on remaining polio-endemic countries in its
efforts to eradicate the disease on time by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"The countdown for the year 2000 goal of poliomyelitis (polio)
eradication has begun in earnest," said Bjorn Melgaard, Chief of
the WHO Expanded Program on Immunization.
</P>
<P>
"Failure in one country is global failure," Melgaard warned his
audience at the end of a week-long session at the United Nations
specialized agency's headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
"We must focus our efforts on the remaining polio-endemic
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
The polio virus is still circulating widely in densely
populated countries in three areas: Bangladesh, India, Nepal, and
Pakistan in South Asia; the Democratic Republic of Congo and
Nigeria in West and Central Africa; and Ethiopia, Somalia and
Sudan in the horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the just concluded WHO meeting said a deadly
combination of a shortfall in funds and an overdose of complacency
can jeopardize the global campaign in the final stages.
</P>
<P>
"We are virtually on the home-stretch and we badly need the
second wind to finish on time," said Bruce Aylward, in charge of
the WHO Global Polio Eradication Initiative.
</P>
<P>
"The program is already fully functioning even in Afghanistan
and Somalia," Aylward said.
</P>
<P>
But unless all countries are certified polio-free, he said, "we
can not stop routine polio immunization nor can we start enjoying
the benefits of polio eradication to the tune of 1.5 billion
U.S. dollars which will be saved each year." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
