<HEADLINE> Mandela's Ex-Wife Denies Leaving ANC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Winnie Madikizela-Mandela,
ex-wife of South African President Nelson Mandela, Sunday denied
categorically the reports that she intended to quit the ruling
African National Congress (ANC).
</P>
<P>
"I am the ANC and I will die as the ANC," she said in a
statement sent to South African Press Association (SAPA) office
in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Times reported that Madikizela-Mandela, currently
leader of the ANC Women's League, had sent a letter to the
party's leadership, threatening to quit the National Executive
Committee, citing bad treatment at the hands of top ANC members.
</P>
<P>
Among the leaders mentioned were Sports Minister Steve Tshwete
who wrote an article last year calling her a "liar" and "a
wayward charlatan".
</P>
<P>
This was after she publicly criticized the ANC for failing to
address crime, land redistribution and the shortage of housing.
