<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Import Raw Sugar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
decided to import 46,200 metric tons of raw sugar from Thailand
this month, using minimum access volume in-quota process, a senior
agriculture official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Secretary William Dar said that the volume, to be
levied with 50 percent tariff, is part of the 200,000 metric tons
of raw sugar imports recommended by former agriculture secretary
Salvador Escudero last year.
</P>
<P>
Dar said that President Joseph Estrada will be issuing an order
for the National Food Authority (NFA) to push through with the
importation sometime this month.
</P>
<P>
Industry officials, however, have still to conduct
consultations on the approval for the importation of 153,800
metric tons more of raw sugar, according to Dar.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts said the resumption of sugar imports signaled
the balance between the demand and the supply of the commodity in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines suffered a serious sugar glut in 1997 because
of the over-importation of sugar in late 1996 and in early 1997.
The glut forced the domestic sugar industry to slash sugar prices,
plunging the industry into a crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
