<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Political uncertainty in Japan
took its toll on Australian shares Monday with the market losing
more than one percent amid choppy trade.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index fell 29.3 points, or 1.07
percent, to 2,718.6. The index reached a low for the day of
2,710.8 and a high of 2,747.9.
</P>
<P>
Volatility was inspired by trade in Japan. Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto offered to resign Monday after support
for his ruling Liberal Democratic Party dropped from 61 seats to
44 in the upper house elections on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index finished down 14.3 points, or 1.34
percent, to 1,051.7 while the all industrials index finished down
48.4 points, or one percent, to 4,782.5.
</P>
<P>
Australian resources giant BHP ended the day down 15.3 cents to
14.057 Australian dollars and global miner Rio Tinto lost 30 cents
to 18.35 Australian dollars as copper prices continued to plumb
lows not seen for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
The banking index lost 58.7 points, or 0.97 percent, to 5,970.6
against a background of weaker bond prices.
</P>
<P>
Westpac bank lost 24 cents to 10.24 Australian dollars, ANZ
bank shed 26 cents to 11.27 Australian dollars, National Australia
Bank gained five cents to 22.50 Australian dollars and
Commonwealth Bank gained one cent to 19.86 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed down 15.6 points, or 1.45 percent, to
1,059.6. Gold bullion closed at 289.25 U.S. dollars, well down
from Friday's official close of 291.10 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overall, national turnover was 214.44 million shares, valued at
500.15 million U.S. dollars and falls outnumbered rises 644 to
323. 
</P>
