<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Falls on Japanese PM's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar tumbled
Monday in response to political uncertainty in Japan.
</P>
<P>
In its first local trading session following a shock weekend
election result in which Japan's Liberal Democratic Party won just
44 seats, well below the 69 it needed to gain a majority, the
Australian dollar shed over one U.S. cent in short time to bottom
at 60.29 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The move followed the U.S. dollar's surge to over 144 yen.
</P>
<P>
However, stabilization in the yen later the day supported the
local dollar to its close in Sydney of 60.74 U.S. cents, from
61.38 U.S. cents last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto Monday shouldered the
blame for the election result, announcing his resignation but no
successor has yet been chosen.
</P>
<P>
That leaves a caretaker government in charge which puts Japan's
much needed economic reforms on hold at least in the near term.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished at 86.57 Japanese yen, from
Friday's close of 86.84, and at 1.0979 German marks from 1.1221.
</P>
</TEXT>
