<HEADLINE> Millionaires Emerging in Rural Areas in Tibet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Gunggy Cering, a Tibetan driver in
Gongbogyamda County of the Tibet Autonomous Region, has become a
topic among his fellow villagers for his recent spending 190,000
yuan purchasing a new Dongfeng truck.
</P>
<P>
It is the 44-year-old man's ninth updating of his trucks in the
past 12 years since he started a long-distance transport business.
</P>
<P>
Gunggy Cering is one of the millionaires emerging in Tibet with
the rapid economic development in the region.
</P>
<P>
His family now owns a two-story building equipped with modern
domestic electrical appliances including a colored TV and a video
recorder.
</P>
<P>
In one of his large and bright rooms with auspicious designs on
the walls, Gunggy Cering said pridely,"My parents say that our
life is better than that of the serf owners at the time when I
was born."
</P>
<P>
In the middle of this century, 95 percent of the social wealth
in Tibet was controlled by serf owners who accounted for only 5
percent of Tibet's population then.
</P>
<P>
"At that time, it was a fairy tale for ordinary Tibetans to
earn a million yuan a year," Gunggy Cering said.
</P>
<P>
Since the Democratic Reform was carried out in Tibet 40 years
ago, the living standard of overwhelming majority of Tibetans has
been improved.
</P>
<P>
China's Central Government has spent more than 40 billion yuan
in the infrastructural projects in Tibet, involving
transportation, energy, farming and animal husbandry, and
tourism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millionaires Emerging in Rural Areas in Tibet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some of the inland provinces and municipalities also invested
more than 4 billion yuan in more than 100 projects for the
benefits of Tibetans in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
The projects in transportation, energy, livestock breeding,
agriculture and tourism have laid a solid foundation for the
Tibetans to do their business and become prosperous.
</P>
<P>
Wangjug, another Tibetan millionaire at Bainang County of Xigaze
Prefecture, said, "Depending on the favorable policies of the
state and my diligence, I am becoming well off."
</P>
<P>
Wangjug, who started his business on a small sum of funds in
the late 1980s, bought a computer to help manage his business.
</P>
<P>
He has a dozen trucks for transportation and he was also a
contractor for building projects. His fixed assets exceeded 4
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
In Dengqen County of Qamdo Prefecture, Yungzong Sita has
managed two stores, one in the county seat and the other in rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
He developed his business on the basis of a bank loan of 1,500
yuan two decades ago. Now his assets top 1 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
In Qamdo Prefecture, there are more than 10,000 business people
among the 500,000 herdsmen and more than 100 Tibetans have become
millionaires.
</P>
<P>
Yungzong Sita is trying his best to help villagers in Bazha
Township to eliminate poverty. To date, 50 Tibetan
families have achieved prosperity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
