<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Funds Boosts China's Hydropower Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- China has 23 hydropower projects
in operation or under construction by utilizing foreign funds
worth nearly 3.7 billion US dollars, with a total generating
capacity over 18.84 million kw.
</P>
<P>
"China has the richest hydro-electric power resources in the
world, with exploitable water energy resources estimated at 376
million kw, ranking first in the world," said a senior official
with the State Power Corporation of China.
</P>
<P>
The official said that China has completed 13 hydropower
projects with a combined generating capacity of 5.62 million kw by
using 1.44 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Five others, with a total capacity of 8.1 million kw, are being
built with 1.4 billion US dollars worth of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
China has been developing its hydro-electric power industry for
four decades, but especially since the reforms and opening-up
drive began in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Total generating capacity and annual electricity output have
risen from 163,000 kw and 710 million kwh. This makes China third
in generating capacity and production in the world.
</P>
<P>
However, the official said, there is still a lot that needs to
be done to make use of China's enormous resources. Its total
generating capacity accounts for only 13.8 percent of what is
possible.
</P>
<P>
According to China's medium-and long-range development plans,
it will have a capacity of 70 million kw by the year 2000, and by
2010, that will rise to 125 million kw, or 33.1 percent of the
country's exploitable hydro-electric power resources.
</P>
<P>
The official said that 3.5 million kw will be added annually,
on average, in the remaining years of the century, and from 2000
to 2010, hydro-electric power capacity will increase by five
million kw annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
