<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Ministerial Meeting to Focus on Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming ASEAN Ministerial
Meeting and its related meetings will put focus on the current
economic situation and its implications on the countries within
Asia, as well as those beyond the region.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Foreign Affairs Secretary Domingo Siazon made this
announcement at a press briefing on the 31st ASEAN (Association of
Southeast Asian Nations) Ministerial Meeting (AMM) and its related
meetings -- the Post Ministerial Meeting (PMC) and the 5th ASEAN
Regional Forum -- to be held from July 20 to 29.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said the prolonged financial crisis, combined with the
economic slowdown and the problems of structural reforms in Japan,
has led many to "believe that the region's optimism for continued
economic prosperity over the next two to three years has become
ambiguous at best."
</P>
<P>
"We are witnessing what might be the most defining moment for
the post-cold war world -- a re-evaluation of current economic and
financial architectures; a new perspective on the role of major
economic powerhouses and emerging economies; and the swift
judgment of markets in the electronic global markets," Siazon
said.
</P>
<P>
At such a moment, Siazon said, the AMM and its related meetings
are an incomparable opportunity to put focus on the current
economic situation and consider its implications on the countries
within Asia, as well as those beyond the region.
</P>
<P>
The AMM and PMC will provide the opportunity for ASEAN
economies directly affected to consider the causes of the
financial crisis and the crisis' implications with the ASEAN
dialogue partner countries, particularly the major players -- the
United States, Japan, China and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Another issue of concern that becomes relevant in the AMM and
PMC, among ASEAN and its dialogue partners, is the financial
turmoil's concurrent effects on the social system of ASEAN, Siazon
said.
</P>
<P>
Besides the regional currency crisis and its effect, the AMM
and PMC will also tackle Cambodia, nuclear proliferation in South
Asia, and transnational crime, according to Siazon.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said Cambodia, whose admission by ASEAN was deferred in
July 1997 due to its political instability, is a key to the
realization of the dream of ASEAN 10.
</P>
<P>
Siazon promised to push the earlier acceptance of Cambodia by
ASEAN if the country conducts free, fair and peaceful general
elections.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN presently groups the Philippines, Brunei, Vietnam, Laos,
Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia, Indonesia and Myanmar. The
Philippines holds the current rotating ASEAN chairmanship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Urged to Be Integrated With Asian Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Now is not the time for Australia
to withdraw from the Southeast Asian region, "we have been
integrated, it cannot be reversed," according to Thai Foreign
Minister Surin Pitsuwan.
</P>
<P>
Surin, who is paying an official visit in Sydney, told
reporters Monday that "no country is an island," engagement,
integration and cooperation were the answers to the problems in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Surin said he was in Australia to familiarize himself with the
nation's current views on the Asian financial crisis, "and to try
and convince Australian business that there is an opportunity up
there (in Asia)," he was quoted by the Australian Associated Press
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We've tried to turn the crisis into an opportunity and I think
we have been quite successful. The message that I would like to
impart to the businessmen down here in Australia is to stay
engaged, because the fundamentals in the economies of Southeast
Asia, particularly in the ASEAN, are still very, very strong," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The manufacturing base is still very much sound, it's the
confidence and the lack of capital, liquidity, that we are
suffering from and we think we will be able, through various
policies, initiatives ... to get out of that in the near future,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Australia was one leg of the tripod of Southeast Asian
prosperity, the other two being Japan and Thailand, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Australia has convinced all of us in Southeast Asia and
Thailand that you belong to the region and this is not the time to
withdraw or to shrink back because if there is a vacuum there will
be others who will want to fill the vacuum," Surin said.
</P>
<P>
Surin said he would meet with Foreign Minister Alexander Downer
Tuesday to discuss a number of issues, including the political
situation in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"We have been very close in cooperation over Cambodia," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He would also meet with Deputy Prime Minister and Trade
Minister Tim Fischer and Defense Minister Ian McLachlan during his
visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
