<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan to Become Intelligent Island (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Hainan, known as the largest area
open to the outside world in China, is planning to become an
"intelligent island" that vanguards the country's transfer into
knowledge economy in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
The island, matching Taiwan in size, boosts the largest number
of mobile telephones owned by every hundred urban residents among
all cities in the country. An on-line booking system that the
island first adopted has now been widely used in the country for
tourism services.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest plan of the south-most island province
of China, it will draw one-fifth of its GDP from information
industry by 2010. In that year, 80 percent of the households in
the island will be hooked with a wide-band network that combines
functions of telephone, computer and television in one. The whole
island will be covered with an intelligent network that extends to
all aspects of economy, social management and public life.
</P>
<P>
Zhan Changzhi, director of the information economy office of
Hainan province, said that this is not an unattainable target
because China has embarked on an irreversible course to a
knowledge economy.
</P>
<P>
In the beginning of the next century, China will become the
second largest market of personal computers and the largest user
of telephone lines in the world.
</P>
<P>
Hainan and other coastal areas have taken the lead in turning
China into a information economy. Since the beginning of the
1990s, Hainan has invested more than four billion yuan (482
million US dollars) in laying two optical fiber cables between the
island and the mainland, building a satellite station and
developing a circuit of wide-band cables around the island.
</P>
<P>
In the end of 1996, the island opened the Hainan Public
Information Network, an Internet-based network connecting
governmental institutions, enterprises and individual users.
</P>
<P>
Huo Yiwei, a key developer of the network, said that it was
designed to multiply efficiency of resources by facilitating
smooth flow of information.
</P>
<P>
The governmental administration system and statistics system,
which are part of the network, have played an important role in
rationalizing the decision-making process. The systems give
government officials access to accurate and prompt information of
the society and economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan to Become Intelligent Island (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The information network has made life more convenient for
island residents and greatly facilitated the operation of local
enterprises. Citizens of Haikou city, capital of Hainan, use IC
card instead of cash to pay their medical bills. Island residents
can open an account at a bank and make settlement through any one
of the five major commercial banks in the island.
</P>
<P>
Local township enterprises have successfully found business
partners in the other semisphere on Internet.
</P>
<P>
Xing Ming, manager of the Hainan Agricultural Information
Network, said that the on-line service provider enrolls a dozen of
users every day among local enterprises that are eager to
advertise their products on internet.
</P>
<P>
An official from the provincial government said that
development of an information economy is more than building
infrastructures and networks. He said that the most important
thing is to reform the mode of management.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government set up the Information Economy Office
to push forward this reform last year. As part of cross-province
education program, all civil servants under the age of 45 and
applicants for becoming civil servants must have training in
computer application.
</P>
<P>
Zhan said that Hainan attracts talents with beautiful
environment, open policies and flexible systems.
</P>
<P>
"We will be able to catch up with and surpass advanced
economies as long as we have adequate talents," he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, Hainan has become a newly rising information
industrial center in China, following Beijing, Shanghai,
Guangzhou, Shenzhen and Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
In March, China's largest software sales company announced to
move its headquarters to Hainan. Many international IT companies
such as Microsoft, IBM, Compaq, NEC and Lotus are discussing with
Hainan on cooperative projects.
</P>
<P>
As the largest special economic zone in China, Hainan is
building a model of information society of the 21st century for
China. It plans to invest ten billion yuan (1.2 billion US
dollars) in building a information economy in the last five years
of this century.
</P>
<P>
Hainan will focus on the development of IT equipment
manufacturing and software and system integration.
</P>
<P>
Zhan said that Hainan has set a target of becoming a "software
island." A software production base has already start operation in
March and undertaken a 2-million-US-dollar contract for a Japanese
company.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Revises GDP Growth to Negative for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim announced Monday the
revision of the country's gross domestic product (GDP) growth to a
negative rate of 1.0 percent to 2.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Based on the current domestic and external economic
developments, the government has reviewed estimates for GDP
growth for the whole of this year," he said while announcing
fiscal stimulus and additional measures to restore economic growth
in Parliament here Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Given the economic performance in the first quarter
and the latest economic indicators, it is highly likely that the
contraction in real GDP will increase if there is no action or new
measures introduced to stimulate economic growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said based on the country's economic performance to date
and given that regional financial markets have yet to recover,
the estimated 1998 GDP growth rate estimated at between 2 percent
and 3 percent was now clearly difficult to achieve.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's annualized real GDP growth in the first quarter of
the year has contracted by 1.8 percent, a negative GDP growth for
the first time in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the Malaysian manufacturing sector, the engine of
the country's economy, had registered a decrease of 5 percent in
the first five months of this year due to the reduced quantity of
exports to the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of this year, Malaysian exports
dropped by 10.3 percent in U.S. dollars mainly because exports
from the country to other ASEAN countries and Japan fell by 22.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
"All these developments have forced the government to take
immediate and direct action to revive the country's economy," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the current balance of payments account is expected to
strengthen as the country had registered a trade surplus of 16.2
billion ringgit (3.82 billion U.S. dollars) for the first five
months of this year compared with 48.5 million ringgit (11.438
million dollars) achieved in the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
He said exports increased from January to May this year at a
rate of 40.5 percent in terms of ringgit value, which is higher
than the increase of 20.8 percent in imports.
</P>
<P>
He said for the whole of 1998 trade account is expected to
register a surplus of 30 billion ringgit (7.075 billion dollars),
which is more than enough to balance the deficit in the service
account by 25 billion ringgit (5.896 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
This will make it possible for the current balance of payments
to register a surplus of 2 billion ringgit (471.698 million
dollars) or one percent of the GDP, which would be the first
surplus in trade since the last 10 years, he added.
</P>
<P>
Anwar also said that the inflation rate for 1998 is projected
at between 7.0 percent and 8.0 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
