<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Fund Manager Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- China has set up a new fund
management company, the fifth so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The Boshi Fund Management Co. Ltd., approved by the China
Securities Regulatory Commission (CSRC), has been jointly
sponsored by the China Greatwall Trust and Investment Company, Jinhua
City Trust and Investment Co. Ltd., Guoxin Securities Co. Ltd
and Everbright Securities Co. Ltd. It has a registered capital
of 100 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Agricultural Bank of China (ABC) has been
designated by the CSRC and the People's Bank of China, the central
bank, as qualified for the trusteeship of securities investment
funds.
</P>
<P>
To meet the new need, the bank has set up a new department in
charge of fund trusteeship business.
</P>
<P>
ABC, one of China's big-four state-owned commercial banks, had
total assets valued at 1.57 trillion yuan at the end of 1997. It
currently has more than 65,000 subsidiaries across China.
</P>
<P>
China has issued and listed four securities investment funds
to date, all closed-end and at two billion yuan each. The fifth
is expected to be issued soon.
</P>
<P>
The second group of five securities investment funds are also
scheduled to be issued in the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of investment funds indicates China's
determination to develop institutional investors to ensure the
stable development of the securities market, analysts say.
</P>
</TEXT>
