<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Making Efforts to Bring Levy Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai has met former Foreign Minister David Levy to ask him to
rejoin the cabinet, Israel Radio reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The radio said Mordechai held several-hour talks with Levy
Sunday and expected him to resume his previous post as foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
But it did not say if Levy had accepted the offer.
</P>
<P>
The Mordechai-Levy meeting was part of the efforts made by
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to prepare for a decision over
the next redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
As a deal seems near on the U.S. proposal for a 13.1 percent
Israeli withdrawal, Netanyahu is trying to secure its passing in
future parliamentary vote.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Netanyahu, whose right-wing coalition
partners have threatened to topple his government if he adopts the
U.S. proposal, will strengthen his position on a pullback if Levy
returns to the government.
</P>
<P>
The Levy-led Gesher Party is owning five seats in the
120-member Knesset (Parliament), without which the Likud coalition
has only the slim 61-seat majority.
</P>
<P>
Under the Israeli law, the government will step down if 61
lawmakers vote against it.
</P>
<P>
Levy, a leading moderate who supports an Israeli withdrawal
from the West Bank, resigned in January over a dispute with
Netanyahu on the 1998 budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
