<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise in Tokyo Despite LDP's Setback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed sharply higher
in Tokyo Monday despite the devastating setback of Japan's Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) in Sunday's House of Councillors election.
</P>
<P>
Stocks plunged across the board in the opening minutes of
trading, but it later rebounded on buybacks by foreign brokerages
and bargain-hunting by Japanese institutions.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange ended at 16,360.39, up 270.33
points, or 1.68 percent, from last Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, advanced 14.94 points or 1.20 percent to
1,256.44.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the First Section came at an estimated 390 million
shares, down from 597.78 million shares Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
While traders admitted surprise at the LDP's poor election
performance, some said it could turn out to be a blessing as the
government may be forced to come up with more effective policies
to spur the sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
Some traders said buying was spurred by the fact that the
Nikkei index had already taken a large fall of 356.89 points last
Friday, partly due to apprehension over Sunday's elections.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outpaced losers 710 to 447, with 119 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar fell nearly
three yen on profit-taking at one point after having hit as high
as 144.50 yen on the LDP's election defeat.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 142.40-43 yen at 5 p.m. (local
time), down from 144.05-07 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo, but up from
141.30-40 yen late Friday in New York.
</P>
<P>
To take responsibility for the LDP's election defeat, Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto offered to step down on Monday
afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
