<HEADLINE> Russian Prime Minister in Tokyo to Seek Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko arrived here Monday to seek more economic aid needed for
helping Russia tide over the current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko, the first Russian premier to visit Japan, is
scheduled to talk with outgoing Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto and Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
He would also meet Japanese business leaders during his two-day
stay, before furthering his trip to China.
</P>
<P>
The Russian premier is expected to remind his Japanese
counterpart the need to carry forward a bilateral economic
cooperation program known as the "Hashimoto-Yeltsin Plan."
</P>
<P>
The timing of his visit coincided with Hashimoto's announced
resignation both as the prime minister and the head of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) earlier Monday.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said he would step down to take the blame of the
LDP's setback in Sunday's House of Councillors election.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Kiriyenko is also expected to sign
unofficially with his Japanese counterpart an agreement on
protecting and promoting the mutual investment.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on the establishment of a proposed joint
investment company is also expected to be on his agenda. 
</P>
