<HEADLINE> Turkey to Open Bid for Lucrative Arms Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is to invite 17 foreign arms
companies to bid for a lucrative deal to produce the unmanned
aerial surveillance systems, which will cost 350 million
U.S. dollars, a newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Daily News said the list of foreign bidders being prepared
by the Undersecretariat for Defense Industries, which oversees
Turkey's weaponry production, includes some leading arms producers
from Belgium, Britain, France, Israel, Spain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The report did not disclose when the bid would be opened for
the tenders.
</P>
<P>
But it said that among the 17 companies, the Israeli and
U.S. contenders have higher chances of winning the bid. It added
that the Israeli Aircraft Industries (IAI) and U.S. General
Dynamics Corporation were likely to join hands in defeating other
rivals.
</P>
<P>
Israel has forged a close relationship with Turkey since the
two sides signed a defense cooperation deal in early 1996. The
IAI, armed with advanced electronic and technical expertise, has
been upgrading dozens of Turkish fighter planes.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Turkey is expected to buy a total of 23
unmanned aerial surveillance systems, including 15 long-range and
eight medium-range ones, to increase the early-warning ability of
its army.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the Turkish army bought one such system from the
General Dynamics at the cost of 14 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
