<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia: Production Up, Foreign Trade Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The first half of the year saw
minor output increases in Mongolia's industrial and agricultural
sectors, but a major downturn in the country's export volume.
</P>
<P>
Pushed up by hikes in the mining, leather and garment
industries, said the State Bureau of Statistics, industrial output
was up 2.1 percent over the first six months of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, with 9.7 million new born lambs already in the herd
by July 1, 527,000 more than the same period last year, the total
is expected to be a record high of 10 million for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
However, as shown by the bureau's latest report available
Monday, the foreign trade volume from January through June was
down 2.2 percent to an equivalent of 371.6 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The most noticeable was a 29.4 percent plunge in exports, to
140.9 million dollars, in the six-month period, as results of deep
cuts in prices for copper and cashmere at the international market.
</P>
<P>
Also in the year's first half, there was a 28.1 percent jump in
the country's imports, to 230.7 million dollars, leaving a
half-year unfavorable trade imbalance worth 89.9 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In June, the consumer index climbed 9.2 percent over that at
the end of December, the first time below 10 percent since 1991.
</P>
<P>
And on the government side, budget deficit rose by 3.2 million
dollars, to 32.4 million dollars, in the first six months of the
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Shift Domestic Debt from Short to Long </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
will launch two Treasury Bonds on August 3 to raise six billion
Shillings (96 million U.S. Dollars) a month and shift government
domestic borrowing from short to long term.
</P>
<P>
The stock of domestic debt held in 91-day Treasury Bills stood
at 26.4 billion Shillings (425 million Dollars) in May, according
to a report from the East African weekly newspaper on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The low denomination Treasury Bearer Bond will start at 10,000
Shillings (166 Dollars ) and go up to 50,000 Shillings (833
Dollars ) and 100,000 Shillings (1,666 Dollars).
</P>
<P>
It would be sold monthly from August and will attract an
interest rate above that offered by commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The bond is expected to mature after one year but can be
rediscounted at the CBK or traded in the Nairobi Stock Exchange,
making it a very liquid instrument.
</P>
<P>
The other one is a floating rate two-year Treasury Bond and is
similar to the existing one-year bond. It will be in
denominations of 100,000 Shillings and will also be traded at the
Nairobi Stock Exchange as existing bonds.
</P>
<P>
The interest paid will be 0.5 percent above the 12 weeks
moving average of the 91-days T-Bills at the previous quarter.
This means the interest will be paid quarterly.
</P>
<P>
The need to shift from short to long term was announced by
Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae in his budget speech at
parliament on June 11.
</P>
<P>
At the time, he said, the government would begin the difficult
task of fiscal adjustment that seeks to "lengthen maturity of
domestic debt by encouraging conversion of the bulk of Treasury
Bills to Treasury Bonds."
</P>
<P>
The target is to tap long-term investment funds from the
insurance industry in accordance with the recent amendments to
the Insurance Act requiring companies to hold at least 20 percent
of their long-term investments in government securities.
</P>
<P>
The bond will also qualify for use as an amnesty bond for tax
evaders as set out in Nyachae's budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
