<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Offers to Resign After Election Defeat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto offered to step down Monday for the Liberal Democratic
Party's (LDP) defeat in the House of Councillors election.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto announced his decision to quit as LDP president, and
hence Japanese prime minister, at an extraordinary meeting of the
ruling party's executives in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"I conveyed my intention to resign as party president (and
prime minister) at a meeting of party executive members," he told
a televised press conference.
</P>
<P>
On the LDP's defeat in the triennial race for the upper house
of parliament, he said: "It's all my fault."
</P>
<P>
The LDP, led by Hashimoto since September 1995, suffered a
devastating setback in the upper house poll by winning only 44
seats, short of its targeted 61 pre-election seats.
</P>
<P>
Prime minister from January 1996, Hashimoto became the first
premier to resign to take the blame for a defeat in an upper house
election since the late Sousuke Uno did so in 1989.
</P>
<P>
He also told the press conference that he would cancel his
planned official visits to France and the United States, initially
scheduled for between this Sunday and July 25.
</P>
<P>
"I can't go ahead when I'm resigning," Hashimoto said.
</P>
<P>
Following in his footsteps, the LDP's three top executives --
Secretary General Koichi Kato, Policy Research Council Chairman
Taku Yamasaki, and General Council Chairman Yoshiro Mori --
expressed their readiness to step down, LDP officials said.
</P>
<P>
The LDP, which still dominates the more powerful House of
Representatives, or lower house of parliament, is expected to
convene a meeting of all its parliamentarians in the both houses
on July 27 at the earliest, and calls for a vote to elect the
prime minister at the outset of an extraordinary parliamentary
session, expected later this month, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi and former Chief Cabinet
Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama are the likely candidates to become
Hashimoto's successor, LDP sources said.
</P>
<P>
The major cause of LDP's defeat, analysts said, was its
perceived failure to pull the nation out of its protracted
economic mire.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's resignation may further destabilize Japan's
political and economic situation, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 07:45 </DATE_TIME>
