<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Export up in First Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, the largest port city
in China, exported 15.88 billion U.S. dollar-worth of goods in the
first half of this year, up 13.8 percent over the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
But the growth rate dropped by 15.2 percentage points as a
result of impact exerted by the Asian financial crisis, said a
municipal trade official.
</P>
<P>
Except a 7.2-percent rise in trade with Japan, the city's
export to the Republic of Korea and the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) recorded a sharp decline in the first six
months. But the city's import from Malaysia, the Philippines and
Thailand increased by a big margin.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's export to Europe increased by 36.1 percent while
that to North America up by 24.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises continued to be the backbone of the
city's export with their export value reaching 9.7 billion
U.S. dollars up to the end of June. The export of foreign-funded
firms rose 20.1 percent at 6.3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Export of processed goods has slowed down with a total export
value of 7.2 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
