<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment Advances Coal-Rich Shanxi's Basic Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 13 (Xinhua) --North China's Shanxi Province,
dubbed as a "sea of coal", has introduced an increasing volume of
overseas investment to advance growth of its basic industries.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, most of the overseas investment
has flown into agriculture, telecommunications, technical
upgrading, high-tech and housing construction fields.
</P>
<P>
By now, the agriculture sector of the province has made a use
of 600 million U.S. dollars overseas investment for financial
projects of water diversion and soil preservation on the Loess
Plateau, efficient irrigation, dry farming and poverty relief.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the comprehensive agricultural
development projects at the middle range of the Taihang Mountains,
financed by loans provided by an international agricultural
development fund, has added 17,600 hectares of farmland to the
poverty-hit counties in the Taihang Mountains, benefiting 500,000
local poor people.
</P>
<P>
One fourth of the investment for the fast growth of this
northern Chinese province's telecommunications sector has come
from overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
The Wanjiazhai water diversion project, which will divert water
from the Yellow River, China's second longest, to water-deficient
Shanxi and will cost 20 billion yuan (2.41 billion U.S. dollars),
has won loans worth 400 million US dollars from World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project will divert water to Taiyuan,
the provincial capital, and the second phase to Shuozhou and
Datong, two major cities in northern Shanxi. The project is
expected to be completed in year 2001.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the New World Group of Hong Kong has invested
one billion yuan in building expressways and constructing
residential quarters in cities since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The conglomerate plans to pump up an additional three billion
yuan for construction of more infrastructure facilities in Shanxi
in the coming three to four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
