<HEADLINE> China Tightens Control Over Currency Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- China has been increasing its
crackdown on smuggled currency at border checkpoints since the
beginning of this year with satisfactory results, "People's Daily"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Customs House in south China's Guangdong Province solved 60
cases of currency smuggling with a total value of 30.29 million
yuan, and 60,000 counterfeit U.S. dollars in the first half of
this year.
</P>
<P>
One driver, named Zhuang, hid 17 different kinds of foreign
currencies worth 10.39 million yuan RMB under the driver's seat as
he passed Guangdong Province's Huanggang checkpoint, which borders
on the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) on June 24 and
was caught there by customs officials.
</P>
<P>
The Nanjing Customs House made arrests in 11 currency smuggling
cases involving 1.128 million yuan RMB, 180,000 HK dollars and
285,200 U.S. dollars in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a passenger named Qian was seized attempting to leave
China with more than 100,000 yuan RMB in undeclared cash at Lukou
International Airport in Nanjing recently.  
</P>
</TEXT>
