<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Million People Affected by Floods in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 2 million people have been
affected and 1 million acres of crops damaged by floods in
Bangladesh since the monsoon season began in July, press reports
here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Water levels in all the major rivers in the country continued
to rise due to heavy downpour and onrush of water from the
upstream, and the continuously rising water of the Padma, Meghna,
Jamuna, Brahmaputra, Madhumati, Teesta, Atrai, Karotoa and Gorai
rivers had submerged fresh areas, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Padma Sunday crossed the danger level at the Aricha point,
some 70 kilometers northwest of here, and might cross the red
marks Monday. The Jamuna might cross the danger level at the
Sirajgonj point, about 110 kilometers northwest of here, Monday if
the inflow of water continued.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of people had to abandon their homes and
took shelter on the flood protection embankments and highlands,
suffering from scarcity of food, drinking water, fuel and
medicine, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Low-lying areas were submerged due to heavy rainfall in Cox's
Bazar and Banderban, southeast Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
In Cox's Bazar, at least 100 houses, shops and business centers
at the district headquarters had been submerged as the Bakkhali
river crossed the red mark Sunday, and some 300,000 people had
been affected.
</P>
<P>
In Tangail, 80 kilometers northwest of the capital, floods
forced about 5,000 people to leave their homes, and a vast tract
of land and homesteads in low-lying areas were under water, with
about 10,000 acres of paddy, jute and groundnut damaged.
</P>
<P>
And about 10,000 people in the northeastern Roopganj district,
100,000 people in the southern Barisal district, and 37,000 people
in Sirajgonj have been affected by floods.
</P>
<P>
There are frequent heavy rains in the monsoon season (from July
to October) in the South Asian nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
