<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Calls for More Int'l Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim said Monday the Asian crisis reveals quite
starkly that the current level of international cooperation is
inadequate for international trade liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and the other affected countries pointed this out at
the start of the crisis and the international community was
finally coming round to it, Anwar, who is also finance minister,
said when opening the International Management Accounting
Conference/National Accountants' Conference here.
</P>
<P>
"It is now generally agreed that there is a need to strengthen
or even overhaul international supervisory frameworks so that
contagious crises could be avoided in the future and the
likelihood of a global recession thereby reduced," he said.
</P>
<P>
There is no compelling reason to believe that the current
crisis, serious though it is, would protract far into the next
millennium, especially with so much energy being concentrated on
resolving it, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said there was every reason to believe that borders would
continue to break down and the world would continue to shrink.
"For better or for worse, globalization will accelerate as
information technology, which is its main ally, continues to
develop at a relentless pace," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said globalization would mean stiffer competition and this
naturally called for transparency, accountability and
professionalism which all subsumed good corporate governance.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the principle of creative destruction called for the
rebuilding of a more reliable system which meant, among others,
that accounting management and corporate governance must be given
more attention than before by both the public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference "Organizational Challenges into the New
Millennium" is jointly organized by the Malaysian Institute of
Accountants and the Faculty of Business Management of Universiti
Kebangsaan (National University) Malaysia and attracts over 400
delegates from Australia, Canada, New Zealand, South Africa,
Britain, Brunei and Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
