<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Loses 133,333 Ha of Farmland to Other Purposes in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- China lost 135,800 hectares of
farmland to other purposes in 1997, today's "People's Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Land and Natural Resources, last
year the country's farmland was cut by 462,333 hectares due to
construction, structural adjustment in agriculture and natural
disasters, but 326,466 hectares of farmland was added by way of
land reclamation. Therefore, the total loss stood at 135,800
hectares.
</P>
<P>
The imbalance shows that the trend toward farmland shrinkage
has not been fully brought under control in China, though the
country has long worked out a goal for realizing a balance in the
gross volume of agricultural land, and it last year started
to freeze the construction of non-farming projects that may occupy
present farmland.
</P>
<P>
An official from the ministry blamed the farmland shrinkage on
loopholes in the management of construction and the ineffective
implementation of state policies.
</P>
<P>
localities have been urged to strictly follow the state policy
of ensuring a farmland balance, construct projects on idle land,
concentrate construction of more projects in one place, and better
monitor the approval of licenses to those agricultural projects
that may occupy too much farmland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
