<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian and Chinese Gymnasts
wrested most of the medals from the 1998 Pacific Alliance
Gymnastics Championships in Winnipeg, Canada this weekend.
</P>
<P>
Of the 43 medals up for grabs in the team competition,
individual all-around, and apparatus finals, China won 14,
including the men's team gold, and Australia 13.
</P>
<P>
Among the 12 Pacific Rim countries competing, Australia and
China were the only two to record multiple top-three finishes in
both men's and women's events.
</P>
<P>
Kym Dowdell, the tournament's technical director, said: "China
did not send their strongest teams."
</P>
<P>
Australian Andrei Kravtsov captured the men's all-around title,
and he and teammate Bret Hudson both won gold in event finals.
</P>
<P>
Australian Zeena McLaughlin finished second in the women's
all-around, winning gold on balance beam and silver on floor
exercise.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. girls won the team trophy and found themselves on the
podium six times.
</P>
<P>
U.S. national champ Vanessa Atler shone Sunday, snatching two
gold medals.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 Pan American Games will be held in Winnipeg next
summer. 
