<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Financial Sector Operates Smoothly in First Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Statistics released today by the
People's Bank of China (PBOC) show that the financial sector has
been operating quite smoothly during the first half of this year,
with bank loans and deposits steadily increasing and the yuan RMB
remaining stable.
</P>
<P>
The statistics show that by the end of June the amount of broad
money (M2) was 9.4656 trillion yuan, up 14 percent from the same
period last year; the outstanding amount of narrow money (M1) was
3.3776 trillion yuan, up 8.7 percent; and money in circulation
(M0) was 972 billion yuan, up 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months, money withdrawn from circulation
amounted to 45.76 billion yuan, an increase of 77.7 billion yuan
over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, the amount of outstanding loans from
various financial institutions was 7.8797 trillion yuan, up 15.6
percent over the same period last year, or 0.4 percentage higher
than at the end of May.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, medium- and long-term loans
increased by 71.28 billion yuan, of which, those extended to
infrastructure construction increased by 61.2 billion yuan, an
increase of 17.1 billion yuan over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Since April, medium- and long-term loans have gained momentum,
indicating that governmental measures to increase infrastructure
investment and expand domestic demand are being implemented.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, total deposits reached 8.6894 trillion
yuan, up 15.2 percent over the same period last year, among which,
enterprise deposits accounted for 2.7979 trillion yuan, up 11.5
percent, while personal deposits were 4.9948 trillion yuan, up
16.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The statistics show that deposits increased 415.6 billion yuan
in the first half of this year, some 16.5 billion yuan more than
that in the same period last year. And state-owned commercial
banks continue to enjoy strong payment capability.
</P>
<P>
At the end of June, the exchange rate of the yuan RMB against
the U.S. dollar remained stable, at one U.S. dollar per 8.2797
yuan RMB. The foreign exchange market experienced a balance of
supply and demand, according to these statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
