<P>
TOKYO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto formally announced his resignation as premier Monday
afternoon to take the blame for the LDP's defeat in Sunday's House
of Councillors election.
</P>
<P>
"I am taking the blame for the big defeat," Hashimoto said at a
televised press conference.
</P>
<P>
The LDP suffered a major setback in the triennial upper house
race by winning only 44 seats, failing to retain what it called
its targeted 61 pre-election seats.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the major cause of LDP's defeat was the failure
of its economic policies.
</P>
<P>
The resignation of Hashimoto may further destabilize Japan's
political and economic situation.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi and former Chief Cabinet
Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama are the likely candidates to become
Hashimoto's successor, LDP sources said.
</P>
<P>
Until a successor is selected, Hashimoto is expected stay on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
