<HEADLINE> Mahuad Wins Victory in Ecuador Presidential Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, July 12 (Xinhua) -- The 48-year-old mayor of Quito,
Jamil Mahuad, was elected Ecuador's next president in the run-off
election Sunday, an exit poll showed.
</P>
<P>
Mahuad, from the centrist Christian Democratic Union, received
51.2 percent of the vote, compared to 48.8 percent for banana
tycoon Alvaro Noboa who ran as an independent, according to the
poll sponsored by television stations.
</P>
<P>
Mahuad emerged with Noboa as the two top winners in the May 31
first-round elections.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador's elections board will release official results on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mahuad, who was a popular mayor of the capital city Quito until
he took leave to run the the presidency, will take office on
August 10 for a four-year term.
</P>
<P>
The president-elect, born in the town of Lojo near the Peruvian
border, holds a Harvard degree in public administration. His
grandfathers immigrated from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The elections, the biggest in the country's history, was
monitored by international observers from Argentina, Bolivia,
Brazil, Canada, Mexico, Paraguary, the United States, Uruguay, and
the Organization of American States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
