<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guizhou May Be Original Birthplace of Giant Panda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- After analyzing a large collection
of giant panda fossils, archaeologists have concluded that
southwestern China's Guizhou Province may be one of the original
birthplaces of the giant panda.
</P>
<P>
Giant pandas, an endangered species of rare animal, is now
mainly found in southwest China's Sichuan Province, northwest
China's Gansu Province and Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Wu Tianzhuang, an archaeologist at the Guizhou Museum, said a
large amount of ancient giant panda fossils from various
evolutionary periods have been unearthed in his province, dating
from 10,000 to 600,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe the modern giant panda is the result of four
periods of evolution going back as early as 25 million years
ago. Evaluations indicate that the giant panda fossils discovered
in Guizhou cover three of the four period, including those of the
earlist modern giant panda.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that the fossils discovered in various parts of the
province indicate that the giant panda became extinct in Guizhou
10,000 years ago because of a changing climate and the intrusion
of mankind into the region.
</P>
<P>
He added that the simple diet of the giant panda and their low
reproductive capacity are two of the reasons for the decline of
the species. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
