<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China City Endeavors to Resettle Laid-offs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Guangzhou municipal government
will take effective measures to solve laid-off workers' life
difficulties and to create re-employment opportunities for them.
</P>
<P>
The city will go all out to implement policies it mapped out
last year, including guaranteeing minimum wages for all employees,
the minimum subsidy for laid-off workers, minimum unemployment
welfare money and a minimum living standard, to protect their
basic lifestyles, said Mayor Lin Shusen.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou, the capital of south China's Guangdong province,
began to take its privately-run enterprises, township enterprises
and individual business runners into its pension and social
insurance program early in July in an attempt to alleviate the
pressure on the government to solve its laid-off workers' life
problems and to seek a way to rid its employees of their worries
about unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Lin noted that the city will set up more employment service
centers to find job vacancies for laid-off workers and it will
extend the service network even to the grassroots.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he added, the municipal government will set aside
more funds for the program to train laid-off workers to make it
possible for them to find new jobs that they are unfamiliar with.
</P>
<P>
The city's goal is to find new job vacancies for 60 percent of
the laid-off workers annually and keep the unemployment rate below
three percent in the foreseeable future, he said.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou registered 80,000 laid-off workers in the first
quarter of this year, and it created 31,800 job opportunities for
them, an increase of 17.7 percent over the same period in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Sets up Anti-Harassment Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has set up an
Anti-Harassment Committee to provide 24-hour service to deal with
public complaints of harassment by elements in the security
forces.
</P>
<P>
A press release by the Presidential Secretariat stated that
representations had been made to the President that some officers
had been responsible for the harassment of Tamil persons who were
arrested or detained for questioning.
</P>
<P>
It said the President is aware that the majority of officers
execute their responsibility with great restraint and humanity
under extremely trying conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, numerous reports have been received that some
officers indulge in unnecessary harassment of Tamil detainees
contrary to instructions.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly President Chandrika Kumaratunga has appointed a
Committee of Ministers and Senior Members of Parliament to look
into representations made by persons harassed or not dealt with
accordingly to the law so that immediate action could be taken to
grant them relief.
</P>
<P>
The Committee is empowered to give directions to any head of
the armed forces or the police force in regard to any illegal
arrest or undue harassment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
