<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Commerce Ministry Plans Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Commerce Ministry is
working out a restructuring program aimed at focusing on export
promotion and trade negotiation to cope with the fast changing
economic situation, according to Sompol kietphaibool, Permanent
Secretary to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
The plan is to remove overlapping tasks and amend 42 trade
laws under the ministry's jurisdiction. One of the planned reforms
is to eliminate redundancy in overseas offices. For instance,
Commercial Affairs Office (CAO) and Thai Trade Center (TTC) are
currently under the control of the Office of Permanent Secretary
for Commerce and Export Promotion Department, but both units
perform similar tasks on export promotion and trade negotiation,
Sompol was quoted Monday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the target, 40 CAO offices operating abroad will be
reduced.
</P>
<P>
Initially, the Department of Export Promotion will be reformed
 and a trade Development Council will be set up to function with
authority similar to that of the Board of Investment Committee.
</P>
<P>
The council may be chaired by the prime minister to make
important policies.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, unnecessary regulations will be reviewed to
strengthen exports. This will streamline export procedures and
increase efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the Department of Business Economics (DBE) will be
renamed the International Trade Negotiation Department. In the
future, both multilateral and bilateral negotiations will be the
responsibility of the department.
</P>
<P>
Currently, multilateral agreements such as the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation will fall under the DBE while bilateral
agreement such as the Thai-U.S. Textile Agreement will fall under
the Department of Foreign Trade (DFP).
</P>
<P>
The department will set up an Economics and International Trade
Research Office to provide updated databases. This will help the
country prepare strategies to strengthen the country's
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will modernize 42 trade laws written around World
War ii. Personnel will be retrained to increase efficiency and
skills, especially information technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
