<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Quality Standards for Flower Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of
Agriculture has drafted a set of quality standards as a key
measure to stimulate the domestic flower industry and gain a
large share in the international market, according to "China
Daily" today.
</P>
<P>
An official with the ministry is quoted as saying that the
standards will help improve the overall quality of flowers and
ensure a safer trade order.
</P>
<P>
Flower production has boomed in China during the last decade in
the wake of improvement in the people's living standards.
</P>
<P>
Flower shops have mushroomed, enjoying increasingly brisk
business, while street vendors with buckets of flowers have become
a common sight at rush hours.
</P>
<P>
However, problems such as slow improvement in the quality of
flowers and low flower prices for the growers have cropped up
endangering the development of the fledging industry.
</P>
<P>
The official said that in a sense, the quality standards will
protect flow growers' interests so that they can increase their
production and improve the quality of flowers.
</P>
<P>
According to him, quality standards for cut roses,
gypsophila, gladioli, carnations and chrysanthemums have been
published. Quality standards for 30 other flowers will also be
published by the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
China's high-quality flowers and 70-80 percent of flower
seedlings are imported.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is also improving statistical and information
service as part of its efforts to promote the sector's
development. It will set a national statistical network on line
for the flower-growing sector next year in cooperation with the
State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The network, which now has 40 big member units ranging from
administrative departments, flower growers to flower traders, will
provide both the growers and traders with latest flower
information.
</P>
<P>
China has 80,000 hectares of land devoted to flower planting,
accounting for one third of the world's total. And it has plenty
of ancient and typical species. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
