<HEADLINE> New Power Projects in Guangdong be Bid Out Publicly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- All new power projects scheduled
for construction in coming years in south China's Guangdong
Province will be built through public bidding nationwide, "China
Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Total investment for these new plants, which will have an
installed capacity of more than 6 million kilowatts, will outstrip
60 billion yuan (7.23 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The province tries to attract foreign investors to finance
local power industry, which still has great potential in the years
ahead because of the rapid economic growth in southern China, the
paper quoted an official from the Guangdong Electricity Group Corp
as saying.
</P>
<P>
These power plants will also import plenty of advanced foreign
equipment and technologies in the future, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Taishan Plant, which has two 660,000-kw generating units,
will cost an investment of 10 billion yuan (1.2 billion
U.S. dollar), while the Shanwei Plant, with two 600,000-kw
generating units, needs 11 billion yuan (1.33 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Guangdong plans to invest a total of 10.9 billion yuan (1.31
billion US dollars) this year in building its power projects. The
investment gap is large, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
