<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises Sharply Against Yen Early in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar climbed above 144
yen in Tokyo early Monday morning following the devastating defeat
of Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) in Sunday's House
of Councillors election.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 144.05-144.07 yen at 9 a.m. (local
time), up from 141.30-141.40 yen late Friday in New York and from
140.95-141.05 yen in London.
</P>
<P>
Early in the morning, the dollar hit a height of 144.50 yen, a
level last seen on June 17 when the United States and Japan
jointly intervened in the currency market to prop up the sagging
yen.
</P>
<P>
The LDP won only 44 of the 126 seats contested, far short of
its targeted 61 seats. Ryutaro Hashimoto has decided to quit as
LDP president and prime minister to take the blame for his party's
major setback.
</P>
<P>
Dealers believe the dollar will move further upward against the
yen.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, meanwhile, share prices plunged
with the key Nikkei index dipping below 16,000 for the first time
on an intraday basis since July 1.
</P>
<P>
In the first 15 minutes of trading, the Nikkei Stock Average of
225 selected issues on the First Section fell 271.23 points, or
1.69 percent, from last Friday's close to 15,818.83.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 17.76 points or 1.43 percent to
1,223.74. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
