<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector in Guangzhou to Have Full Scope for Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The municipal government of
Guangzhou, the capital of south China's Guangdong Province,
encourages the city's private sector to compete in the world
market, according to a number of suggestions to encourage private
sector to conduct foreign trade and economic co-operative
activities passed here recently.
</P>
<P>
The suggestions are the country's first local official effort
to encourage the private sector to get involved in a field long
dominated by state-owned businesses, "China Daily" said here today.
</P>
<P>
A municipal government official urged the myriad private
companies in Guangzhou to earn big profits in the world market and
contribute to the city's economic growth while enlivening the
domestic economy.
</P>
<P>
Private sector is allowed to conduct foreign trade and set up
their overseas subsidiaries and branches in Hong Kong, Macao and
around the world. Their overseas companies and branches will be
treated as foreign firms when they return to invest in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses will be able to set up joint ventures and
Sino-foreign co-operative firms with their overseas
partners. Government departments should provide necessary
services. Those who have the status of "legal person" will receive
the same preferential policies as state-owned enterprises in
conducting processing business supplied by foreign partners.
</P>
</TEXT>
