<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hashimoto to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto will announce his resignation as premier and president
of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) to take
responsibility for the LDP's major setback in Sunday's House of
Councillors election, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto will offer the resignation at a meeting of LDP
executives later Monday, Kyodo quoted a senior LDP official as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, in a televized speech, said late Sunday that the
setback suffered by the LDP is his responsibility entirely and he
will decide what to do about it.
</P>
<P>
The LDP is expected to end up with less than 55 seats, far
short of its 61 seats being contested in Sunday's upper house
election, according to an exit poll conducted by Kyodo.
</P>
<P>
If Hashimoto resigns, Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi and former
Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama are the likely candidates
to become his successor, Kyodo quoted LDP sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The LDP also plans to ask some opposition parties, including
the New Peace Party and the Komei party, to join hands with the
LDP in a partial alliance.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto was scheduled to visit France and the United States
from July 19 but the election result may change this, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto has indicated the 61 LDP seats at stake as a win-loss
line. LDP Secretary General Koichi Kato expressed similar views.
</P>
<P>
The LDP fielded 87 candidates, 30 for the proportional
representation slots, under which voters cast their ballots for a
party rather than for an individual, and 57 for prefectural
constituencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980713.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's LDP Suffers Major Setback in Upper House Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP) suffered a major setback in Sunday's election for the
House of Councillors (upper house) losing 17 seats, official
figures showed Monday.
</P>
<P>
As of 2 a.m. local time Monday (1700 GMT, Sunday), 44 LDP
candidates had been declared wining, 30 in prefectural
constituencies and 14 in the proportional representation system,
far short of its 61 seats being contested in the triennial
election.
</P>
<P>
The figure was the second worst only after the 36 seats won by
the LDP in the 1989 election.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest reason (for the LDP setback) is a delay in
economic recovery," Taku Yamasaki, chairman of the LDP's Policy
Research Council, said in a television program.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hahshimoto is expected to
announce his resignation as LDP president and hence prime minister
to take responsibility for his party's crushing setback.
</P>
<P>
A senior LDP official confirmed that Hashimoto has decided to
announce his intention to quit the LDP presidency and the prime
ministership at LDP executives' meeting later Monday.
</P>
<P>
In stark contrast to the LDP's disastrous showing, Japan's
largest opposition Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ), headed by
popular former Health and Welfare Minister Naoto Kan, was headed
for a conspicuous advance.
</P>
<P>
The DPJ, 18 of whose seats were being contested, appeared
certain to break the 30 mark, including seats for DPJ-backed
candidates.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Communist Party (JCP), whose public support has
reached record highs recently, also emerged as a big winner in the
race by doubling its strength in the upper house.
</P>
<P>
By 2 a.m. Monday, 26 DPJ aspirants had been declared
successful, 14 for the JCP, nine for the Komei party, six for the
Liberal Party (LP) and five for the Social Democratic Party
(SDP). A total of 20 independents also were declared winners.
The New Party Sakigake did not pick up any seats.
</P>
<P>
Half of Japan's upper chamber, which has far less clout than
the lower house in determining the government formation or
policies, is reshuffled every three years, with members serving a
fixed six-year term.
</P>
<P>
About 99.40 million people -- 48.24 million men and 51.16
million women -- were eligible to vote in Sunday's poll.
</P>
<P>
Voter turnout was projected at 58.27 percent, up sharply from a
record low 44.52 percent posted in the previous election in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The sharp recovery in voter turnout was traced to the extension
of voting hours by two hours under a revision of the Public Offices
Election Law last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
