<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, July 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- Leaders of Northern Ireland's Protestant Orange Order
pledged on Sunday to scale down protests across Northern Ireland
against a ban on their parade through a Catholic enclave in
Portadown.
</P>
<P>
The pledge by the Grand Orange Lodge of Ireland came amid
mounting tension in Northern Ireland after eight days of violence
by Protestant extremists that culminated in a firebomb attack
early Sunday that killed three Catholic children. (Orange
Order-Protests)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto will
announce his resignation as premier and president of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) to take responsibility for the
LDP's major setback in Sunday's House of Councillors election,
Kyodo News reported. (Japan-Hashimoto-Resignation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko and a
delegation from the International Monetary Fund have "agreed on
all key issues" on a multi-billion-U.S.-dollar financial bail-out
for Russia, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko's meeting with the delegation led by John
Odling-Smee, head of the IMF department responsible for the former
Soviet Union ended later Sunday, Itar-Tass said quoting a
government source. (Russia-IMF-Loan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei Sunday
rejected the recent U.S. overture as a "normal political
hypocritical ploy."
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Secretary of State Madelaine
Albright said last month that Washington is ready to end 20-year
hostility with Iran. Khamenei said Washington's overture was based
on its miscalculated analysis of Iran's domestic political
situation. (Iran-Khamenei-US Overture) 
</P>
