<HEADLINE> Key Northern Afghan Province Seized by Taliban: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia have
claimed to have captured a key province in northern Afghanistan
after a major offensive and amid intense infighting in the
opposition Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here Sunday night from the Afghan
capital of Kabul, the Taliban had earlier claimed sweeping gains
against the Northern Alliance with the capture of Faryab province.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia were reported to be fighting their way to
Mazar-e-Sharif, the stronghold of the anti-Taliban Northern
Alliance led by ousted Afghan president Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
One report quoted a senior Afghan official for information and
culture Maulawi Mohammad Yaqub as saying that "after we launched a
heavy attack, the whole of Faryab has been taken and the
mujahedeen have advanced into Jowzjan."
</P>
<P>
"There has been little resistance, and the opposition were just
fleeing for their lives, leaving behind all their heavy weapons,"
Yaqub said.
</P>
<P>
However, Yaqub's claim could not have been independently
confirmed. Meanwhile, officials from the Northern Alliance said
that they were unable to comment.
</P>
<P>
Faryab was a major stronghold of Rashid Dostam, an important
ally of the anti-Taliban Northern Alliance. However, Dostam's grip
over the area is reported to be weak due to long standing disputes
with local commanders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
