<HEADLINE> Orange Order Plans to Scale down Protests in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 12 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of Northern Ireland's
Protestant Orange Order pledged on Sunday to scale down protests
across Northern Ireland against a ban on their parade through a
Catholic enclave in Portadown.
</P>
<P>
"Taking immediate effect peaceful protests will be scaled
down," the Orange Order said in a statement in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The pledge by the Grand Orange Lodge of Ireland came amid
mounting tension in Northern Ireland after eight days of violence
by Protestant extremists that culminated in a firebomb attack
early Sunday that killed three Catholic children.
</P>
<P>
The Grand Lodge said it wanted its annual province-wide
celebrations on Monday to take place "in a dignified fashion and
which, mindful of the recent tragedy, will fully recognize local
sensitivities."
</P>
<P>
The independent Parades Commission has agreed to allow the
Orangemen's parade to take place in Belfast on Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, the Grand Lodge said it backed its Portadown members'
decision to have "a continued presence at Drumcree".
</P>
<P>
Earlier Orangemen in Portadown voted to continue the Drumcree
protest indefinitely, despite calls for it to end after the arson
attack.
</P>
<P>
Garvaghy Road residents' spokesman Breandan MacCionnaith said
the Orangemen's decision showed that the Portadown Orange Order
was "beyond anyone's control."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
